{"title_page": "List of botanical gardens in Russia", "text_new": "'''Botanical gardens in Russia''' have collections consisting entirely of Russia native and [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species; most have a collection that include plants from around the world. There are botanical gardens and [[Arboretum|arboreta]] in all states and territories of Russia, most are administered by local governments, some are privately owned.\n* [[Botanical Garden of V.L. Komarov Botany Institute RAS (BIN)]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n* [[Botanic Garden of the Irkutsk State University]]<ref>[http://bogard.isu.ru/indexe.htm]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071030002306/http://library.thinkquest.org/05aug/01907/botan.htm]</ref>[[Irkutsk]]\n* [[Botanical Garden of Academy of Sciences]], [[Moscow]]\n* [[Botanical Garden of Moscow State University]], [[Moscow]]\n* [[Gorky Park (Taganrog)|Taganrog Botanical Garden]], [[Taganrog]]\n* [[List of Botanical Gardens and Arboreta of Russia]] <ref>[https://archive.is/20130703230223/http://www.caspianenvironment.org/biodiversity/rus/annex7.htm]</ref>\n* [[VILAR Botanical Garden]], [[Moscow]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Russia|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of botanical gardens by country|Russia]]\n[[Category:Lists of biota of Russia|Botanical gardens]]\n[[Category:Lists of tourist attractions in Russia|Botanical gardens]]\n", "text_old": "'''Botanical gardens in Russia''' have collections consisting entirely of Russia native and [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species; most have a collection that include plants from around the world. There are botanical gardens and [[Arboretum|arboreta]] in all states and territories of Russia, most are administered by local governments, some are privately owned.\n* [[Botanical Garden of V.L. Komarov Botany Institute RAS (BIN)]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n* [[Botanic Garden of the Irkutsk State University]]<ref>[http://bogard.isu.ru/indexe.htm]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071030002306/http://library.thinkquest.org/05aug/01907/botan.htm]</ref>[[Irkutsk]]\n* [[Botanical Garden of Academy of Sciences]], [[Moscow]]\n* [[Botanical Garden of Moscow State University]], [[Moscow]]\n* [[Gorky Park (Taganrog)|Taganrog Botanical Garden]], [[Taganrog]]\n* [[List of Botanical Gardens and Arboreta of Russia]] <ref>[https://archive.is/20130703230223/http://www.caspianenvironment.org/biodiversity/rus/annex7.htm]</ref>\n* [[VILAR Botanical Garden]], [[Moscow]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Russia topics}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Russia|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of botanical gardens by country|Russia]]\n[[Category:Lists of biota of Russia|Botanical gardens]]\n[[Category:Lists of tourist attractions in Russia|Botanical gardens]]\n", "name_user": "Paul 012", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv irrelevant navbox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_botanical_gardens_in_Russia"}
{"title_page": "Malinda S. Smith", "text_new": "{{short description|Political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Malinda S. Smith\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        =\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = \n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Athabasca University]] (until 2004)|University of Alberta}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Western Michigan University]]|[[University of Alberta]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| thesis_title      =Power, ideology and the construction of the Contra/revolution.\n| thesis_year       = 1993\n| known_for         = \n| awards            =\n}}\n'''Malinda Sharon Smith''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[political scientist]]. She is a professor of political science at the [[University of Alberta]], where she is also a [[Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation]] Fellow and a Provost Fellow in Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion. She specialises in [[Multiculturalism|diversity]] and [[intersectionality]] studies, particularly as they are practiced in [[higher education]] institutions, as well as [[Africa]]n [[security studies]] and [[international inequality]].\n\n==Career==\n===Education===\nSmith holds a BA and an MA in political science from [[Western Michigan University]], and a PhD from the University of Alberta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://calendar.athabascau.ca/undergrad/2000/faculty16.html |title=Faculty, Professional Staff and Tutors |publisher=Athabasca University |date=1 January 2000 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Before joining the faculty at the University of Alberta in 2004, she was a professor at [[Athabasca University]] in [[Athabasca, Alberta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parliamentary-democracy.athabascau.ca/introduction/team.html |title=Module on Parliamentary Democracy |publisher=Athabasca University |last=Stewart |first=David |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nSmith has been the editor or co-editor of 6 books. She was the sole editor of ''Globalizing Africa'' (2003), ''Beyond the African Tragedy: Discourses on Development and the Global Economy'' (2006), and ''Securing Africa: Post-9/11 Discourses on Terrorism'' (2010).<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/arts/about/people-collection/malinda-s-smith |title=Professor Listing Malinda S. Smith |publisher=University of Alberta |year=2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Many of Smith's articles in peer-reviewed journals have focused on diversity, equity, and inclusion in academia, including systematic studies of diversity among the leadership of the [[U15 Group of Canadian Research Universities]] and the recipients of the [[Canada Research Chair]] program.<ref name=cbc>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/researcher-diversity-study-1.5207654 |title=Canada's top researcher positions continue to lack diversity, U of A study finds |date=13 July 2019 |work=[[CBC News]]|last=Zoledziowski |first=Anya |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=globe>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-canada-research-chairs-program-taking-new-measures-to-close-equity/ |title=Canada Research Chairs program taking new measures to close equity gaps among prestigious academic positions |date=31 July 2019 |work=The Globe and Mail |last=Hannay |first=Chris |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSmith's work has been cited, or she has been quoted on topics related to her work, in news outlets like [[CBC News]],<ref name=cbc/> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'',<ref name=globe/> ''[[The Toronto Star]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/09/26/st-albert-fire-chief-suspended-for-two-weeks-over-blackface-incident.html |title=St. Albert fire chief suspended for two weeks over blackface incident |publisher=The Toronto Star |date=26 September 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[Maclean's]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.macleans.ca/education/why-30-more-female-professors-still-isnt-good-enough/ |title=Why 30% more female professors still isn't good enough |date=4 May 2017 |work=Maclean's Magazine |last=Smith |first=Madeline |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and ''[[La Rotonde]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.larotonde.ca/universites-racistes-canada/ |language=fr |title=L'universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa, les seuls \u00e1 bl\u00e2mer? |date=24 June 2019 |work=La Rotonde |last=benimana |first=Alex |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Positions===\nSmith has been the President and the Vice President of the Canadian regional branch of the [[International Studies Association]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.csa-scs.ca/conference/conference-events/event/conference-keynote-dr-malinda-smith/ |title=Conference Keynote: Dr. Malinda S. Smith |publisher=Canadian Sociological Association |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and was its 2018 Distinguished Scholar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/political-science/about-political-science/news/2017/august/malinda-smith-named-distinguished-scholar |title=Dr. Malinda Smith named International Studies Association - Canada Distinguished Scholar, 2018 - 2019  |publisher=International Studies Association, Canada |date=25 August 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> She has also been the Vice President for Equity Issues at the [[Canadian Federation for the Humanities and Social Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rabble.ca/news/2011/07/equity-aboriginal-education-only-way-forward |last=Smith |first=Malinda S. |title=Equity in Aboriginal education is the only way forward |publisher=Rabble |date=7 July 2011 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> as well as a Provost Fellow in Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion Policy at the University of Alberta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.congress2020.ca/calendar/1079 |title=Diversity Gap in Canadian Higher Education |publisher=Congress 2020 |year=2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Smith was named the inaugural Vice Provost (Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion) at the [[University of Calgary]] in Calgary, Alberta, with a starting date in August 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ucalgary.ca/news/dr-malinda-smith-appointed-vice-provost-equity-diversity-and-inclusion |title=Dr. Malinda Smith appointed vice-provost (equity, diversity and inclusion) |publisher=University of Calgary |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nSmith received the 2015 Equity Award of the [[Canadian Association of University Teachers]] for \"outstanding contributions to equity and collective bargaining\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caut.ca/latest/2015/12/caut-awards-presented-professors-malinda-s-smith-and-rolland-gaudet |title=CAUT awards presented to professors Malinda S. Smith and Rolland Gaudet |publisher=Canadian Association of University Teachers |date=1 December 2015 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Smith was also named a 2018 Fellow of the Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation; the Foundation gives $225,000 distributed over 3 years<ref name=uapet>{{cite web |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/arts/faculty-news/2018/june/political-scientist-malinda-s-smith-named-2018-pierre-elliott-trudeau-foundation-fello.html |title=Political Scientist Malinda S. Smith named 2018 Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation Fellow |publisher=University of Alberta |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>  to \"five fellows each year in recognition of outstanding achievement, innovative approaches to issues of public policy, and commitment to public engagement\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trudeaufoundation.ca/en/about/publications/info-source |title=The Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation |publisher=Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The purpose of Smith's Fellowship was to support her book project, ''A Seat at the Table: Engendering Black Canadian Pasts and Futures'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fondationtrudeau.ca/en/community/malinda-s-smith |title=Malinda S. Smith |publisher=Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation |year=2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> which aims to centre [[Black Canadians]] in Canada's [[national myth|national stories]] about its legal, political, and educational systems.<ref name=uapet/>\n\n==External links==\n# [http://www.thediversitygapcanada.com Diversity Gap website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Malinda S.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian women academics]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:Western Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:Athabasca University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta faculty]]\n[[Category:Canadian political scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Malinda S. Smith\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        =\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = \n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Athabasca University]] (until 2004)|University of Alberta}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Western Michigan University]]|[[University of Alberta]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| thesis_title      =Power, ideology and the construction of the Contra/revolution.\n| thesis_year       = 1993\n| known_for         = \n| awards            =\n}}\n'''Malinda Sharon Smith''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[political scientist]]. She is a professor of political science at the [[University of Alberta]], where she is also a [[Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation]] Fellow and a Provost Fellow in Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion. She specialises in [[Multiculturalism|diversity]] and [[intersectionality]] studies, particularly as they are practiced in [[higher education]] institutions, as well as [[Africa]]n [[security studies]] and [[international inequality]].\n\n==Career==\n===Education===\nSmith holds a BA and an MA in political science from [[Western Michigan University]], and a PhD from the University of Alberta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://calendar.athabascau.ca/undergrad/2000/faculty16.html |title=Faculty, Professional Staff and Tutors |publisher=Athabasca University |date=1 January 2000 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Before joining the faculty at the University of Alberta in 2004, she was a professor at [[Athabasca University]] in [[Athabasca, Alberta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parliamentary-democracy.athabascau.ca/introduction/team.html |title=Module on Parliamentary Democracy |publisher=Athabasca University |last=Stewart |first=David |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nSmith has been the editor or co-editor of 6 books. She was the sole editor of ''Globalizing Africa'' (2003), ''Beyond the African Tragedy: Discourses on Development and the Global Economy'' (2006), and ''Securing Africa: Post-9/11 Discourses on Terrorism'' (2010).<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/arts/about/people-collection/malinda-s-smith |title=Professor Listing Malinda S. Smith |publisher=University of Alberta |year=2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Many of Smith's articles in peer-reviewed journals have focused on diversity, equity, and inclusion in academia, including systematic studies of diversity among the leadership of the [[U15 Group of Canadian Research Universities]] and the recipients of the [[Canada Research Chair]] program.<ref name=cbc>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/researcher-diversity-study-1.5207654 |title=Canada's top researcher positions continue to lack diversity, U of A study finds |date=13 July 2019 |work=[[CBC News]]|last=Zoledziowski |first=Anya |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=globe>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-canada-research-chairs-program-taking-new-measures-to-close-equity/ |title=Canada Research Chairs program taking new measures to close equity gaps among prestigious academic positions |date=31 July 2019 |work=The Globe and Mail |last=Hannay |first=Chris |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSmith's work has been cited, or she has been quoted on topics related to her work, in news outlets like [[CBC News]],<ref name=cbc/> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'',<ref name=globe/> ''[[The Toronto Star]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/09/26/st-albert-fire-chief-suspended-for-two-weeks-over-blackface-incident.html |title=St. Albert fire chief suspended for two weeks over blackface incident |publisher=The Toronto Star |date=26 September 2019 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[Maclean's]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.macleans.ca/education/why-30-more-female-professors-still-isnt-good-enough/ |title=Why 30% more female professors still isn't good enough |date=4 May 2017 |work=Maclean's Magazine |last=Smith |first=Madeline |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and ''[[La Rotonde]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.larotonde.ca/universites-racistes-canada/ |language=fr |title=L'universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa, les seuls \u00e1 bl\u00e2mer? |date=24 June 2019 |work=La Rotonde |last=benimana |first=Alex |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Positions===\nSmith has been the President and the Vice President of the Canadian regional branch of the [[International Studies Association]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.csa-scs.ca/conference/conference-events/event/conference-keynote-dr-malinda-smith/ |title=Conference Keynote: Dr. Malinda S. Smith |publisher=Canadian Sociological Association |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and was its 2018 Distinguished Scholar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/political-science/about-political-science/news/2017/august/malinda-smith-named-distinguished-scholar |title=Dr. Malinda Smith named International Studies Association - Canada Distinguished Scholar, 2018 - 2019  |publisher=International Studies Association, Canada |date=25 August 2017 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> She has also been the Vice President for Equity Issues at the [[Canadian Federation for the Humanities and Social Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rabble.ca/news/2011/07/equity-aboriginal-education-only-way-forward |last=Smith |first=Malinda S. |title=Equity in Aboriginal education is the only way forward |publisher=Rabble |date=7 July 2011 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> as well as a Provost Fellow in Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion Policy at the University of Alberta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.congress2020.ca/calendar/1079 |title=Diversity Gap in Canadian Higher Education |publisher=Congress 2020 |year=2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Smith was named the inaugural Vice Provost (Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion) at the [[University of Calgary]] in Calgary, Alberta, with a starting date in August 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ucalgary.ca/news/dr-malinda-smith-appointed-vice-provost-equity-diversity-and-inclusion |title=Dr. Malinda Smith appointed vice-provost (equity, diversity and inclusion) |publisher=University of Calgary |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nSmith received the 2015 Equity Award of the [[Canadian Association of University Teachers]] for \"outstanding contributions to equity and collective bargaining\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caut.ca/latest/2015/12/caut-awards-presented-professors-malinda-s-smith-and-rolland-gaudet |title=CAUT awards presented to professors Malinda S. Smith and Rolland Gaudet |publisher=Canadian Association of University Teachers |date=1 December 2015 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Smith was also named a 2018 Fellow of the Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation; the Foundation gives $225,000 distributed over 3 years<ref name=uapet>{{cite web |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/arts/faculty-news/2018/june/political-scientist-malinda-s-smith-named-2018-pierre-elliott-trudeau-foundation-fello.html |title=Political Scientist Malinda S. Smith named 2018 Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation Fellow |publisher=University of Alberta |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>  to \"five fellows each year in recognition of outstanding achievement, innovative approaches to issues of public policy, and commitment to public engagement\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trudeaufoundation.ca/en/about/publications/info-source |title=The Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation |publisher=Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The purpose of Smith's Fellowship was to support her book project, ''A Seat at the Table: Engendering Black Canadian Pasts and Futures'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fondationtrudeau.ca/en/community/malinda-s-smith |title=Malinda S. Smith |publisher=Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation |year=2018 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> which aims to centre [[Black Canadians]] in Canada's [[national myth|national stories]] about its legal, political, and educational systems.<ref name=uapet/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Malinda S.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian women academics]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:Western Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:Athabasca University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta faculty]]\n[[Category:Canadian political scientists]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malinda_S._Smith"}
{"title_page": "List of botanical gardens in Israel", "text_new": "'''Botanical gardens in Israel''' have collections consisting entirely of Israel native and [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species; most have a collection that include plants from around the world. There are botanical gardens and [[Arboretum|arboreta]] in all states and territories of Israel, most are administered by local governments, some are privately owned.\n* [[Ein Gedi]]\n* [[Jerusalem Botanical Gardens]], [[Jerusalem]]\n* Tel-Aviv University Botanical Garden <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120205113214/http://botanic.tau.ac.il/?lang=en]</ref>\n* Arad Botanical Gardens\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Israel|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of botanical gardens by country|Israel]]\n[[Category:Lists of tourist attractions in Israel|Botanical gardens]]\n", "text_old": "'''Botanical gardens in Israel''' have collections consisting entirely of Israel native and [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species; most have a collection that include plants from around the world. There are botanical gardens and [[Arboretum|arboreta]] in all states and territories of Israel, most are administered by local governments, some are privately owned.\n* [[Ein Gedi]]\n* [[Jerusalem Botanical Gardens]], [[Jerusalem]]\n* Tel-Aviv University Botanical Garden <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120205113214/http://botanic.tau.ac.il/?lang=en]</ref>\n* Arad Botanical Gardens\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Israel topics}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Israel|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of botanical gardens by country|Israel]]\n[[Category:Lists of tourist attractions in Israel|Botanical gardens]]\n", "name_user": "Paul 012", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv irrelevant navbox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_botanical_gardens_in_Israel"}
{"title_page": "The Invention of Lying", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Invention of Lying\n| image          = Invention of lying ver2.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = \n| director       = {{Unbulleted list| [[Ricky Gervais]] | [[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]] }}\n| producer       = {{Unbulleted list| Ricky Gervais | [[Dan Lin]] | [[Lynda Obst]] | Oly Obst }}\n| writer         = {{Unbulleted list| Ricky Gervais | Matthew Robinson }}\n| narrator       = [[Ricky Gervais]]\n| starring       = {{Unbulleted list| Ricky Gervais | [[Jennifer Garner]] | [[Jonah Hill]] | [[Louis C.K.]] | [[Rob Lowe]] | [[Tina Fey]]}}\n| music          = [[Child (band)|Tim Atack]]\n| cinematography = Tim Surhstedt\n| editing        = Chris Gill\n| studio         = {{Unbulleted list| [[Radar Pictures]] | [[Media Rights Capital]] | [[Universal Pictures]] }}\n| distributor    = {{Unbulleted list| [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] | (United States/Canada) | [[Focus Features]] (UK/International) }}\n| released       = {{film date|2009|09|14|[[2009 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2009|10|2|United States}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes <!-- U.S. theatrical release: 100:21 -->\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = US$18.5 million<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/interviewsnews.php?id=58292l | title=The Invention of Lying: Ricky Gervais | publisher=ComingSoon.net | date=2009-08-24}}</ref>\n| gross          = US$32.7 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web | url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2009/INVLY.php | title=Movie The Invention of Lying - Box Office Data | publisher=The-Numbers | accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Invention of Lying''''' is a 2009 American [[Speculative fiction|speculative]] [[romantic comedy]] film written and directed by [[Ricky Gervais]] and [[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]] (in their [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debuts]]). The film stars Gervais as the first human with the ability to lie in a world where people can only tell the truth. The cast includes [[Jennifer Garner]], [[Jonah Hill]], [[Louis C.K.]], [[Rob Lowe]], and [[Tina Fey]].  The film was released in the United States on October 2, 2009.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film is set in an [[Parallel universes in fiction|alternative reality]] in which lying does not exist.\n\nMark Bellison is a [[screenwriter]], in a film industry limited to historical readings because there is no fiction. One night he has a date with the beautiful and [[wealth]]y Anna McDoogles. She tells Mark she is not attracted to him, because of his looks and failing financial situation, but is going out with him as a favor to his best friend, Greg Kleinschmidt.\n\nThe next day, Mark is fired from his job because of the lack of interest in his films (which are set in the lackluster [[14th century]]), and his landlord threatens to evict him for not paying his rent. Crestfallen, he goes to the bank to close his account. The teller informs him that the computers are down and asks him how much money he has in his account. Mark then has an [[Epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]] that enables him to tell the world's first lie, which is that he has $800 \u2014 the amount he owed his landlord \u2014 in his account. He then lies in a variety of other circumstances, initially for personal gain; he prevents a police officer from arresting Greg for [[Driving under the influence|drunk driving]], [[Breaking the bank|breaks the bank]] at a [[casino]], and writes a [[screenplay]] about the world being invaded by aliens in the 14th century that ends with the claim that everyone's memories were erased. He becomes wealthy from the film's success. Mark soon realises that lying can also be used to help others, such as stopping his [[Major depressive disorder|depressive]] neighbour Frank Fawcett from committing [[suicide]]. Soon after, Mark convinces Anna to go out with him again. She congratulates Mark for his financial success and admits that he would be a good husband and father, but she is still not attracted to him due to how his genetics/appearance would not be a good factor in how she wants her child to be/look like.\n\nMark then gets a call that his mother, Martha, has had a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and rushes to the hospital. There, the doctor tells him that Martha is going to die. She is scared of death, believing that it will bring an [[Eternal oblivion|eternity of nothingness]]. Mark, through tears, tells her that death instead brings a joyful [[afterlife]], introducing the concept of a [[Heaven]] to her, and she dies happy. Mark soon receives worldwide attention as the news of his supposed information about death spreads. After encouragement from Anna, he tells the world, through \"ten rules\" (mirroring the [[Ten Commandments]]), that he talks to a \"Man In The Sky\" who controls everything and promises great rewards in the good place after death, as long as you do no more than three \"[[sin|bad things]]\".\n\nSome time later, Anna and Mark are together in a park and Anna asks him, if they marry, if his now being rich and famous would make their children more physically attractive. Mark wants to lie, but does not because of his love for Anna, and says \"No\". Meanwhile, Mark's rival, Brad Kessler, pursues Anna romantically, motivated by his jealousy at Mark's success. Though Brad's selfish and cruel manner makes Anna uncomfortable, she continues dating him and they become engaged. Before the wedding, Greg appears and convinces Mark that he has not missed his chance with Anna. Mark reluctantly attends Anna and Brad's wedding, where he objects to the marriage. The officiant, however, informs him that only the Man in the Sky can stop the wedding. Brad and Anna both ask Mark to ask the Man in the Sky what Anna should do, but Mark refuses to say anything and leaves, wanting Anna to choose for herself. Anna walks out and Mark confesses his ability to lie. Anna struggles to understand the concept and asks why he did not lie to convince her to marry him; Mark states that it \"wouldn't count\". Anna confesses that she loves him.\n\nSome time later, Anna and Mark are shown happily married with a son, who appears by his actions to have inherited his father's ability to lie.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Ricky Gervais]] as Mark Bellison\n* [[Jennifer Garner]] as Anna McDoogles\n* [[Rob Lowe]] as Brad Kessler\n* [[Louis C.K.]] as Greg Kleinschmidt\n* [[Jonah Hill]] as Frank Fawcett\n* [[Christopher Guest]] as Nathan Goldfrappe\n* [[Tina Fey]] as Shelley Bailey\n* [[Roz Ryan]] as Nurse Barbara\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]] as Anthony James\n* [[Jimmi Simpson]] as Bob Scott\n* [[Fionnula Flanagan]] as Martha Bellison\n* [[Shaun Williamson]] as Richard Bellison\n* [[Bobby Moynihan]] as Bellison's Assistant\n* [[Dreama Walker]] as Receptionist\n* [[Ashlie Atkinson]] as Bank Teller\n* [[Martin Starr]] as Waiter\n* [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]] as Landlord\n* [[Donald Foley]] as Yelling Man\n* [[John Hodgman]] as Wedding Overseer\n* [[Nate Corddry]] as News Reporter\n* [[Stephanie March]] as Blonde Woman on the Street\n* [[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]] as Person #4\n* [[Jason Bateman]] as Doctor (cameo)\n* [[Stephen Merchant]] as Man at the Door (cameo)\n* [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]] as Jim The Bartender (cameo)\n* [[Edward Norton]] as Traffic Cop (cameo)\n* [[Karl Pilkington]] as Cave Man (cameo)\n* [[Eric Andre]] as Mansion Man (cameo)\n* [[Donna Sorbello]] as Anna's mother\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\n[[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]]\u2019s script which was titled ''This Side of Truth'' at the time, was included in 2007 official [[Black List (survey)|Black List]] of the \u201cmost liked\u201d un-produced scripts in Hollywood.<ref name=BlackList>{{cite web |title=2007 Black List |url=https://ed1055efa47d74815ce0-826e8a392aaf48b70eb85d8703df9872.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/2007_black_list.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=The Black List, LLC |quote=10th rank with 10 mentions |accessdate=2018-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107120223/https://ed1055efa47d74815ce0-826e8a392aaf48b70eb85d8703df9872.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/2007_black_list.pdf |archivedate=2018-01-07 }}</ref> Robinson and producer [[Lynda Obst]] sent Ricky Gervais the script out of the blue in the hopes that it would spark his interest. Gervais loved it and eventually flew Robinson to London to retool the script and make the movie. Robinson\u2019s original idea for a feature film grew from a skit he wrote about two people on a date who do not have the ability to lie. He later expanded on the idea for more skits with the same premise and then adapted them it into a full film script.<ref>[http://www.ifc.com/2015/05/15-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-the-invention-of-lying 15 THINGS WE BET YOU DIDN\u2019T KNOW ABOUT THE INVENTION OF LYING]</ref>\n\nProduction of the film originally used the title ''This Side of the Truth''.<ref name=\"week63\">{{cite web| url=http://rickygervais.com/thissideofthetruthb.php| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321202626/http://www.rickygervais.com/thissideofthetruthb.php| archive-date=2012-03-21| title=Week sixty-three \u2014 April 2009| accessdate=2009-05-08| work=Ricky Gervais... Obviously| last=Gervais| first=Ricky| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Media Rights Capital]] and Radar Pictures financed the film.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Invention of Lying |url=https://variety.com/2009/film/markets-festivals/the-invention-of-lying-1200477113/ |magazine=Variety.com |first=Justin |last=Chang |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref> However, 1821 Pictures sued Radar Pictures for a breach of payment contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Film Co. Can't Nix 'Invention Of Lying' Contract Suit |url=https://www.law360.com/articles/355326/film-co-can-t-nix-invention-of-lying-contract-suit |publisher=Law 360 |first=Jonathan |last=Randles |date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref> Shooting took place primarily in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]]; location shoots also took place in [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]], [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], [[North Andover, Massachusetts|North Andover]], [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]], [[Tewksbury, Massachusetts|Tewksbury]], [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]],{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} and [[Haverhill, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hollywood in Haverhill; Denzel to film in empty Lowe's building |url=http://www.eagletribune.com/news/hollywood-in-haverhill-denzel-to-film-in-empty-lowe-s/article_7b2e3079-9541-5aff-bf80-a5ff8f72b6e6.html |newspaper=Eagle-Tribune |date=2013-05-23 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] was completed in June 2008.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\n=== Soundtrack ===\nThe soundtrack includes [[Elvis Costello]]'s otherwise-unreleased rendition of the [[Cat Stevens]] song \"Sitting\".\n\nSongs also include: [[Eddie and the Hot Rods]]' \"[[Do Anything You Wanna Do]]\", [[Donovan]]'s \"[[Catch the Wind]]\", [[Supertramp]]'s \"[[Give a Little Bit]]\", and [[Electric Light Orchestra]]'s \"[[Mr. Blue Sky]]\".\n\n== Release ==\n[[Warner Bros.]] owns the rights for the film's North American distribution, while [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] owns the rights to release the film outside of North America. The film was released in North America on October 2, 2009. Its world premiere occurred two weeks earlier at the [[2009 Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 14, 2009.\n\nThe DVD and Blu-ray were released on January 19, 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bluray.ign.com/articles/105/1051539p1.html | title=The Art of Lying | work=[[IGN Entertainment]] | publisher=IGN Movies | date=2009-12-03 | accessdate= 2009-12-26}}</ref> Gervais briefly promoted the DVD during his hosting duty at the [[67th Golden Globe Awards]] in a joking manner, referring to its modest box office results.\n\n== Reception ==\n===Critical reception===\nReview aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 56% of 188 critics have given the film a positive review, with a [[weighted mean|rating average]] of 5.9/10. The site's consensus says, \"It doesn't quite follow through on its promise, and relies too heavily on shopworn romantic comedy tropes, but ''The Invention of Lying'' is uncommonly sly and funny.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/invention_of_lying/ |title=The Invention of Lying |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average rating out of 100 to reviews from film critics, the film has a rating score of 58 based on 31 reviews, suggesting \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/inventionoflying?q=the%20invention%20of%20lying | title = The Invention of Lying (2009): Reviews | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = 2009-12-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' awarded the film three and a half stars out of four saying \"in its amiable, quiet, PG-13 way, [it] is a remarkably radical comedy\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|title=The Invention of Lying|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090930/REVIEWS/909309993|publisher=rogerebert.com|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref>  Xan Brooks of ''[[The Guardian]]'' was also favourable, giving the film four out of five stars, although he was critical of some aspects: \"It is slick and it is funny. But it is also too obviously schematic, while that romantic subplot can feel awfully synthetic at times.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/oct/02/the-invention-of-lying-review ''Invention of Lying'' review] from ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>  [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''The New York Times'' called it a \"mostly funny if melancholic defense of deceit\" that \"looks so shoddy that you yearn for the camerawork, lighting and polish of his shows, like [[The Office (UK TV series)|the original ''The Office'']], because, really, these days TV rarely looks this bad.\"  In some scenes, Dargis says \"lying becomes a means to transcendence, an escape from the quotidian, from our oppressive literal-mindedness, from our brute selves. For the most part, though, Mr. Gervais prefers to shock us with our own brutality...[with] unvarnished truths [that] begin to feel heavy, cruel.\"<ref>{{cite news| title= A World Where Truth Turns Out Not to Be Beauty | url= https://movies.nytimes.com/2009/10/02/movies/02invention.html |author= Manohla Dargis |date= October 2, 2009| newspaper= The New York Times| accessdate=2011-05-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film opened at #5 with US$7,027,472 behind ''[[Zombieland]]'', ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'' in its third weekend, the ''[[Toy Story]]''/''[[Toy Story 2]]'' [[Toy Story 2#Re-releases|3-D double feature]], and ''[[Surrogates (film)|Surrogates]]'' in its second weekend.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/boxoffice/?date=2009-10-02&region=us Internet Movie Database US film charts 2nd October]</ref> The film has grossed US$18,451,251 in the United States, and US$13,955,256 internationally, with a worldwide gross of US$32,406,507.<ref name=\"the-numbers\" /><ref>[http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inventionoflying.htm ''The Invention of Lying''] from [[Box Office Mojo]]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://the-invention-of-lying.warnerbros.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1058017}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|invention_of_lying}}\n* {{Mojo title|inventionoflying}}\n\n{{Ricky Gervais}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Invention Of Lying}}\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Films critical of religion]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ricky Gervais]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Dan Lin]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films with atheism-related themes]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Media Rights Capital films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Ricky Gervais]]\n[[Category:2009 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Invention of Lying\n| image          = Invention of lying ver2.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = \n| director       = {{Unbulleted list| [[Ricky Gervais]] | [[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]] }}\n| producer       = {{Unbulleted list| Ricky Gervais | [[Dan Lin]] | [[Lynda Obst]] | Oly Obst }}\n| writer         = {{Unbulleted list| Ricky Gervais | Matthew Robinson }}\n| narrator       = [[Ricky Gervais]]\n| starring       = {{Unbulleted list| Ricky Gervais | [[Jennifer Garner]] | [[Jonah Hill]] | [[Louis C.K.]] | [[Rob Lowe]] | [[Tina Fey]]}}\n| music          = [[Child (band)|Tim Atack]]\n| cinematography = Tim Surhstedt\n| editing        = Chris Gill\n| studio         = {{Unbulleted list| [[Radar Pictures]] | [[Media Rights Capital]] | [[Universal Pictures]] }}\n| distributor    = {{Unbulleted list| [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] | (United States/Canada) | [[Focus Features]] (UK/International) }}\n| released       = {{film date|2009|09|14|[[2009 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2009|10|2|United States}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes <!-- U.S. theatrical release: 100:21 -->\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = US$18.5 million<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/interviewsnews.php?id=58292l | title=The Invention of Lying: Ricky Gervais | publisher=ComingSoon.net | date=2009-08-24}}</ref>\n| gross          = US$32.7 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web | url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2009/INVLY.php | title=Movie The Invention of Lying - Box Office Data | publisher=The-Numbers | accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Invention of Lying''''' is a 2009 American [[Speculative fiction|speculative]] [[romantic comedy]] film written and directed by [[Ricky Gervais]] and [[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]] (in their [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debuts]]). The film stars Gervais as the first human with the ability to lie in a world where people can only tell the truth. The cast includes [[Jennifer Garner]], [[Jonah Hill]], [[Louis C.K.]], [[Rob Lowe]], and [[Tina Fey]].  The film was released in the United States on October 2, 2009.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film is set in an [[Parallel universes in fiction|alternative reality]] in which lying does not exist.\n\nMark Bellison is a [[screenwriter]], in a film industry limited to historical readings because there is no fiction. One night he has a date with the beautiful and [[wealth]]y Anna McDoogles. She tells Mark she is not attracted to him, because of his looks and failing financial situation, but is going out with him as a favor to his best friend, Greg Kleinschmidt.\n\nThe next day, Mark is fired from his job because of the lack of interest in his films (which are set in the lackluster [[14th century]]), and his landlord threatens to evict him for not paying his rent. Crestfallen, he goes to the bank to close his account. The teller informs him that the computers are down and asks him how much money he has in his account. Mark then has an [[Epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]] that enables him to tell the world's first lie, which is that he has $800 \u2014 the amount he owed his landlord \u2014 in his account. He then lies in a variety of other circumstances, initially for personal gain; he prevents a police officer from arresting Greg for [[Driving under the influence|drunk driving]], [[Breaking the bank|breaks the bank]] at a [[casino]], and writes a [[screenplay]] about the world being invaded by aliens in the 14th century that ends with the claim that everyone's memories were erased. He becomes wealthy from the film's success. Mark soon realises that lying can also be used to help others, such as stopping his [[Major depressive disorder|depressive]] neighbour Frank Fawcett from committing [[suicide]]. Soon after, Mark convinces Anna to go out with him again. She congratulates Mark for his financial success and admits that he would be a good husband and father, but she is still not attracted to him due to how his genetics/appearance would not be a good factor in how she wants her child to be/look like.\n\nMark then gets a call that his mother, Martha, has had a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and rushes to the hospital. There, the doctor tells him that Martha is going to die. She is scared of death, believing that it will bring an [[Eternal oblivion|eternity of nothingness]]. Mark, through tears, tells her that death instead brings a joyful [[afterlife]], introducing the concept of a [[Heaven]] to her, and she dies happy. Mark soon receives worldwide attention as the news of his supposed information about death spreads. After encouragement from Anna, he tells the world, through \"ten rules\" (mirroring the [[Ten Commandments]]), that he talks to a \"Man In The Sky\" who controls everything and promises great rewards in the good place after death, as long as you do no more than three \"[[sin|bad things]]\".\n\nSome time later, Anna and Mark are together in a park and Anna asks him, if they marry, if his now being rich and famous would make their children more physically attractive. Mark wants to lie, but does not because of his love for Anna, and says \"No\". Meanwhile, Mark's rival, Brad Kessler, pursues Anna romantically, motivated by his jealousy at Mark's success. Though Brad's selfish and cruel manner makes Anna uncomfortable, she continues dating him and they become engaged. Before the wedding, Greg appears and convinces Mark that he has not missed his chance with Anna. Mark reluctantly attends Anna and Brad's wedding, where he objects to the marriage. The officiant, however, informs him that only the Man in the Sky can stop the wedding. Brad and Anna both ask Mark to ask the Man in the Sky what Anna should do, but Mark refuses to say anything and leaves, wanting Anna to choose for herself. Anna walks out and Mark confesses his ability to lie. Anna struggles to understand the concept and asks why he did not lie to convince her to marry him; Mark states that it \"wouldn't count\". Anna confesses that she loves him.\n\nSome time later, Anna and Mark are shown happily married with a son, who appears by his actions to have inherited his father's ability to lie.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Ricky Gervais]] as Mark Bellison\n* [[Jennifer Garner]] as Anna McDoogles\n* [[Rob Lowe]] as Brad Kessler\n* [[Louis C.K.]] as Greg Kleinschmidt\n* [[Jonah Hill]] as Frank Fawcett\n* [[Christopher Guest]] as Nathan Goldfrappe\n* [[Tina Fey]] as Shelley Bailey\n* [[Roz Ryan]] as Nurse Barbara\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]] as Anthony James\n* [[Jimmi Simpson]] as Bob Scott\n* [[Fionnula Flanagan]] as Martha Bellison\n* [[Shaun Williamson]] as Richard Bellison\n* [[Bobby Moynihan]] as Bellison's Assistant\n* [[Dreama Walker]] as Receptionist\n* [[Ashlie Atkinson]] as Bank Teller\n* [[Martin Starr]] as Waiter\n* [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]] as Landlor\n* [[Donald Foley]] as Yelling Man\n* [[John Hodgman]] as Wedding Overseer\n* [[Nate Corddry]] as News Reporter\n* [[Stephanie March]] as Blonde Woman on the Street\n* [[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]] as Person #4\n* [[Jason Bateman]] as Doctor (cameo)\n* [[Stephen Merchant]] as Man at the Door (cameo)\n* [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]] as Jim The Bartender (cameo)\n* [[Edward Norton]] as Traffic Cop (cameo)\n* [[Karl Pilkington]] as Cave Man (cameo)\n* [[Eric Andre]] as Mansion Man (cameo)\n* [[Donna Sorbello]] as Anna's mother\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\n[[Matthew Robinson (director)|Matthew Robinson]]\u2019s script which was titled ''This Side of Truth'' at the time, was included in 2007 official [[Black List (survey)|Black List]] of the \u201cmost liked\u201d un-produced scripts in Hollywood.<ref name=BlackList>{{cite web |title=2007 Black List |url=https://ed1055efa47d74815ce0-826e8a392aaf48b70eb85d8703df9872.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/2007_black_list.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=The Black List, LLC |quote=10th rank with 10 mentions |accessdate=2018-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107120223/https://ed1055efa47d74815ce0-826e8a392aaf48b70eb85d8703df9872.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/2007_black_list.pdf |archivedate=2018-01-07 }}</ref> Robinson and producer [[Lynda Obst]] sent Ricky Gervais the script out of the blue in the hopes that it would spark his interest. Gervais loved it and eventually flew Robinson to London to retool the script and make the movie. Robinson\u2019s original idea for a feature film grew from a skit he wrote about two people on a date who do not have the ability to lie. He later expanded on the idea for more skits with the same premise and then adapted them it into a full film script.<ref>[http://www.ifc.com/2015/05/15-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-the-invention-of-lying 15 THINGS WE BET YOU DIDN\u2019T KNOW ABOUT THE INVENTION OF LYING]</ref>\n\nProduction of the film originally used the title ''This Side of the Truth''.<ref name=\"week63\">{{cite web| url=http://rickygervais.com/thissideofthetruthb.php| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321202626/http://www.rickygervais.com/thissideofthetruthb.php| archive-date=2012-03-21| title=Week sixty-three \u2014 April 2009| accessdate=2009-05-08| work=Ricky Gervais... Obviously| last=Gervais| first=Ricky| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Media Rights Capital]] and Radar Pictures financed the film.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Invention of Lying |url=https://variety.com/2009/film/markets-festivals/the-invention-of-lying-1200477113/ |magazine=Variety.com |first=Justin |last=Chang |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref> However, 1821 Pictures sued Radar Pictures for a breach of payment contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Film Co. Can't Nix 'Invention Of Lying' Contract Suit |url=https://www.law360.com/articles/355326/film-co-can-t-nix-invention-of-lying-contract-suit |publisher=Law 360 |first=Jonathan |last=Randles |date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref> Shooting took place primarily in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]]; location shoots also took place in [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]], [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], [[North Andover, Massachusetts|North Andover]], [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]], [[Tewksbury, Massachusetts|Tewksbury]], [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]],{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} and [[Haverhill, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hollywood in Haverhill; Denzel to film in empty Lowe's building |url=http://www.eagletribune.com/news/hollywood-in-haverhill-denzel-to-film-in-empty-lowe-s/article_7b2e3079-9541-5aff-bf80-a5ff8f72b6e6.html |newspaper=Eagle-Tribune |date=2013-05-23 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] was completed in June 2008.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\n=== Soundtrack ===\nThe soundtrack includes [[Elvis Costello]]'s otherwise-unreleased rendition of the [[Cat Stevens]] song \"Sitting\".\n\nSongs also include: [[Eddie and the Hot Rods]]' \"[[Do Anything You Wanna Do]]\", [[Donovan]]'s \"[[Catch the Wind]]\", [[Supertramp]]'s \"[[Give a Little Bit]]\", and [[Electric Light Orchestra]]'s \"[[Mr. Blue Sky]]\".\n\n== Release ==\n[[Warner Bros.]] owns the rights for the film's North American distribution, while [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] owns the rights to release the film outside of North America. The film was released in North America on October 2, 2009. Its world premiere occurred two weeks earlier at the [[2009 Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 14, 2009.\n\nThe DVD and Blu-ray were released on January 19, 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bluray.ign.com/articles/105/1051539p1.html | title=The Art of Lying | work=[[IGN Entertainment]] | publisher=IGN Movies | date=2009-12-03 | accessdate= 2009-12-26}}</ref> Gervais briefly promoted the DVD during his hosting duty at the [[67th Golden Globe Awards]] in a joking manner, referring to its modest box office results.\n\n== Reception ==\n===Critical reception===\nReview aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 56% of 188 critics have given the film a positive review, with a [[weighted mean|rating average]] of 5.9/10. The site's consensus says, \"It doesn't quite follow through on its promise, and relies too heavily on shopworn romantic comedy tropes, but ''The Invention of Lying'' is uncommonly sly and funny.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/invention_of_lying/ |title=The Invention of Lying |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average rating out of 100 to reviews from film critics, the film has a rating score of 58 based on 31 reviews, suggesting \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/inventionoflying?q=the%20invention%20of%20lying | title = The Invention of Lying (2009): Reviews | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = 2009-12-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' awarded the film three and a half stars out of four saying \"in its amiable, quiet, PG-13 way, [it] is a remarkably radical comedy\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|title=The Invention of Lying|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090930/REVIEWS/909309993|publisher=rogerebert.com|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref>  Xan Brooks of ''[[The Guardian]]'' was also favourable, giving the film four out of five stars, although he was critical of some aspects: \"It is slick and it is funny. But it is also too obviously schematic, while that romantic subplot can feel awfully synthetic at times.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/oct/02/the-invention-of-lying-review ''Invention of Lying'' review] from ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>  [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''The New York Times'' called it a \"mostly funny if melancholic defense of deceit\" that \"looks so shoddy that you yearn for the camerawork, lighting and polish of his shows, like [[The Office (UK TV series)|the original ''The Office'']], because, really, these days TV rarely looks this bad.\"  In some scenes, Dargis says \"lying becomes a means to transcendence, an escape from the quotidian, from our oppressive literal-mindedness, from our brute selves. For the most part, though, Mr. Gervais prefers to shock us with our own brutality...[with] unvarnished truths [that] begin to feel heavy, cruel.\"<ref>{{cite news| title= A World Where Truth Turns Out Not to Be Beauty | url= https://movies.nytimes.com/2009/10/02/movies/02invention.html |author= Manohla Dargis |date= October 2, 2009| newspaper= The New York Times| accessdate=2011-05-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film opened at #5 with US$7,027,472 behind ''[[Zombieland]]'', ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'' in its third weekend, the ''[[Toy Story]]''/''[[Toy Story 2]]'' [[Toy Story 2#Re-releases|3-D double feature]], and ''[[Surrogates (film)|Surrogates]]'' in its second weekend.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/boxoffice/?date=2009-10-02&region=us Internet Movie Database US film charts 2nd October]</ref> The film has grossed US$18,451,251 in the United States, and US$13,955,256 internationally, with a worldwide gross of US$32,406,507.<ref name=\"the-numbers\" /><ref>[http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inventionoflying.htm ''The Invention of Lying''] from [[Box Office Mojo]]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://the-invention-of-lying.warnerbros.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1058017}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|invention_of_lying}}\n* {{Mojo title|inventionoflying}}\n\n{{Ricky Gervais}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Invention Of Lying}}\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Films critical of religion]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ricky Gervais]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Dan Lin]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films with atheism-related themes]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Media Rights Capital films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Ricky Gervais]]\n[[Category:2009 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Invention_of_Lying"}
{"title_page": "History of the United Nations", "text_new": "[[File:United Nations member countries  world map.PNG|thumb|500px|alt=A map of the world with countries displayed in colours corresponding to the dates the countries joined the United Nations. Countries not involved with the United Nations are shown in grey.|A map of the world showing when countries joined the United Nations]][[File:UnitedNations.gif|thumb|alt=A black and white motion picture of some men signing papers on a desk in the center of a huge decorated room.|The founding of the [[United Nations]]]]\nThe '''history of the [[United Nations]]''' as an international organization has its origins in [[World War II]]. Since then its aims and activities have expanded to make it the archetypal <span lang=\"te\" dir=\"ltr\">international</span> body in the early 21st century.\n\n==Origins==\nThe earliest concrete plan for a new world organization to replace the ineffective [[League of Nations]] began under the aegis of the [[US State Department]] in 1939.<ref>Townsend Hoopes and Douglas Brinkley, ''FDR and the Creation of the U.N.'' (1997) pp 1-55</ref> On 12 June 1941, representatives of the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the Union of South Africa, and of the exiled governments of Belgium, Czechoslovakia, Greece, Luxembourgtuy, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, and Yugoslavia, as well as a representative of [[Charles de Gaulle|General de Gaulle]] of France, met in London and signed the Declaration of St. James's Palace. This was the first of six conferences that led up to the founding of the United Nations and the Charter of the United Nations.<ref>{{cite web|title=1941: The Declaration of St. James' Palace|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/history-united-nations-charter/1941-declaration-st-james-palace/index.html|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=28 March 2016|date=2015-08-25}}</ref>\n\nU.S. President [[Franklin Roosevelt]] first suggested using the name ''United Nations'', to refer to the [[Allies of World War II]], to British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] during the latter's [[Arcadia Conference|three-week visit]] to the White House in December 1941. Roosevelt suggested the name as an alternative to \"Associated Powers\", a term the U.S. used in the [[First World War]] (the U.S. was never formally a member of the [[Allies of World War I]] but entered the war in 1917 as a self-styled \"Associated Power\"). Churchill accepted the idea and cited [[Lord Byron]]'s use of the phrase \"United Nations\" in the poem ''[[Childe Harold's Pilgrimage]]'', which referred to the Allies at the [[Battle of Waterloo]] in 1815.<ref>{{cite web|title=United Nations|url=http://www.wordorigins.org/index.php/site/comments/united_nations/|website=Wordorigins.org|accessdate=28 March 2016|date=3 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ward|first1=Geoffrey C.|last2=Burns|first2=Ken|title=The Roosevelts: An Intimate History|date=2014|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0385353069|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=V73CAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=SA6-PA60#v=onepage&f=false|chapter=Nothing to Conceal}}</ref>\n\n===1942 \"Declaration of United Nations\"===\n[[File:United Nations \"Fight For Freedom\" poster.jpg|thumb|Poster for the founding of the United Nations]]\n{{main|Declaration by United Nations}}\nThe text of the \"Declaration of United Nations\" was drafted by U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, and Roosevelt aide [[Harry Hopkins]], while meeting at the White House on 29 December 1941. It incorporated Soviet suggestions, but left no role for France. The first official use of the term \"United Nations\" was on 1\u20132 January 1942 when 26 Governments signed the Declaration. One major change from the [[Atlantic Charter]] was the addition of a provision for religious freedom, which Stalin approved after Roosevelt insisted.<ref>David Roll, ''The Hopkins Touch: Harry Hopkins and the Forging of the Alliance to Defeat Hitler'' (2013) pp 172-75</ref><ref>Robert E. Sherwood, ''Roosevelt and Hopkins, An Intimate History'' (1948) pp 447-53</ref> By early 1945 it had been signed by 21 more states.<ref>{{cite book|author=Edmund Jan Osma\u0144czyk|title=Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements: T to Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6AB2CadyN7QC&pg=PA2445|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|page=2445|isbn=9780415939249}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nA JOINT DECLARATION BY THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, THE UNITED KINGDOM OF GREAT BRITAIN AND NORTHERN IRELAND, THE UNION OF SOVIET SOCIALIST REPUBLICS, CHINA, AUSTRALIA, BELGIUM, CANADA, COSTA RICA, CUBA, CZECHOSLOVAKIA, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC, EL SALVADOR, GREECE, GUATEMALA, HAITI, HONDURAS, INDIA, LUXEMBOURG, NETHERLANDS, NEW ZEALAND, NICARAGUA, NORWAY, PANAMA, POLAND, SOUTH AFRICA, YUGOSLAVIA\n<br />\nThe Governments signatory hereto,\n<br />\nHaving subscribed to a common program of purposes and principles embodied in the Joint Declaration of the President of the United States of America and the Prime Minister of Great Britain dated August 14, 1941, known as the Atlantic Charter,\n<br />\nBeing convinced that complete victory over their enemies is essential to defend life, liberty, independence and religious freedom, and to preserve human rights and justice in their own lands as well as in other lands, and that they are now engaged in a common struggle against savage and brutal forces seeking to subjugate the world,\n<br />\nDECLARE:\n<br />\n(1) Each Government pledges itself to employ its full resources, military or economic, against those members of the Tripartite Pact and its adherents with which such government is at war.\n<br />\n(2) Each Government pledges itself to cooperate with the Governments signatory hereto and not to make a separate armistice or peace with the enemies.\n<br />\nThe foregoing declaration may be adhered to by other nations which are, or which may be, rendering material assistance and contributions in the struggle for victory over Hitlerism.<ref>Text from [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/wwii/washc014.asp \"The Washington Conference 1941-1942\"]</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nDuring the war, the United Nations became the official term for the Allies. To join countries had to sign the Declaration and declare war on the Axis.<ref>Stephen C. Schlesinger, ''Act of creation: The founding of the United Nations: A story of superpowers, secret agents, wartime allies and enemies, and their quest for a peaceful world'' (2003)</ref>\n\n===Planning===\n[[File:Early United Nations official's passport from WW2 - working for UNRRA 1944.jpg|thumb|Early United Nations official's passport from World War Two - working for UNRRA, issued in 1944 for the Middle East]]\n[[Foreign policy of the Franklin D. Roosevelt administration|US President Franklin D. Roosevelt]] considered his most important legacy the creation of the United Nations, making a permanent organization  out of the wartime Alliance of the same name. He was the chief promoter of the United Nations idea. The first plans for the future international organization emerged in declarations signed at the wartime Allied conferences: the [[Moscow Conference (1943)|Moscow Conference]] and the [[Tehran Conference]] on 30 October 1943.\n\nRoosevelt had been a strong supporter of the League of Nations back in 1919\u201320, but was determined to avoid the mistakes Woodrow Wilson had made. The United Nations was FDR's highest postwar priority. He insisted on full coordination with the Republican leadership. He made sure that leading Republicans were on board, especially Senators [[Arthur Vandenberg]] of Michigan,<ref>James A. Gazell, \"Arthur H. Vandenberg, Internationalism, and the United Nations.\" ''Political Science Quarterly'' 88#3 (1973): 375-394. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2148990 online]</ref> and [[Warren Austin]] of Vermont.<ref>George T. Mazuzan. ''Warren R. Austin at the U. N., 1946-1953'' (Kent State UP, 1977).</ref> In a broad sense, Roosevelt believed that the UN could solve the minor problems and provide the chief mechanism to resolve any major Issues that arose among the great powers, all of whom had a veto. For FDR creating the UN was the most important goal for the entire war effort.<ref>For FDR,  \"establishing the United nations organization was the overarching strategic goal, the absolute first priority.\" {{cite book|author1=Townsend Hoopes|author2=Douglas Brinkley|title=FDR and the Creation of the U.N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OztJcfbnpDsC&pg=PA178|year=1997|publisher=Yale UP|page=178}}</ref> Roosevelt was especially interested in  international protection of human right, and in this area his wife played a major role as well.<ref>Ivy P. Urdang,  \"Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt: Human Rights and the Creation of the United Nations.\" ''OAH Magazine of History'' 22.2 (2008): 28-31.</ref><ref>M. Glen Johnson,  \"The contributions of Eleanor and Franklin Roosevelt to the development of international protection for human rights.\" '' Human Rights Quarterly'' 9 (1987): 19+.</ref>\n\nThe Allies had agreed to the basic structure of the new body at the [[Dumbarton Oaks Conference]] in 1944.<ref>Hoopes and Brinkley, ''FDR and the Creation of the U. N.'' (1997) pp 148-58.</ref> At Yalta, Roosevelt, Churchill, and Stalin agreed to the establishment of the United Nations, as well as the structure of the [[United Nations Security Council]].  Stalin insisted on having a veto and FDR finally agreed.  The participants at Yalta also agreed that the United Nations would convene for the first time in [[San Francisco]] in April 1945 in the [[United Nations Conference on International Organization]].  Roosevelt considered the United Nations to be his most important legacy. He provided continuous backstage political support at home and with Churchill and Stalin abroad. The Big Four of the United States, Britain, Soviet Union and China would make the major decisions, with France added later to provide permanent members of the all-powerful Security Council. Each had a veto power, thus avoiding the fatal weakness of the League of Nations, which had theoretically been able to order its members to act in defiance of their own parliaments.<ref>John Allphin Moore Jr. and Jerry Pubantz, ''To Create a New World?: American Presidents & the United Nations'' (1999), pp 27-79.</ref>\n \nRoosevelt went public with strong advocacy in the 1944 presidential campaign, and turned detailed planning over to the State Department, where [[Sumner Welles]] and Secretary [[Cordell Hull]] worked on the project. It was his ideas that \"four policemen\" would collaborate to keep and enforce the peace.  The United States, Britain, Soviet Union and China made the major decisions and became permanent members of the all-powerful Security Council; France was added to make five policemen.<ref>Stephen Schlesinger,  \"FDR's five policemen: creating the United Nations.\" ''World Policy Journal'' 11.3 (1994): 88-93. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40209368 online]</ref>  Stalin insisted on a veto power. Roosevelt finally agreed, thus avoiding the fatal weakness of the League of Nations, which theoretically could order its members to act in defiance of their own parliaments.<ref>Townsend Hoopes and Douglas Brinkley, ''FDR and the Creation of the U. N.'' (1997)</ref>\n \nFrom 21 September to 7 October 1944, representatives of the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]], Britain, the US and the [[Soviet Union|USSR]]  met to elaborate plans at the [[Dumbarton Oaks Conference]] in Washington, D.C. Those and later talks produced proposals outlining the purposes of the United Nations organization, its membership and organs, as well as arrangements to maintain international peace and security and international economic and social cooperation. Governments and private citizens worldwide discussed and debated these proposals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/dumbarton_yalta.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016124053/http://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/dumbarton_yalta.shtml |archive-date=2015-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Winston Churchill urged Roosevelt to restore France to its status of a major Power after the liberation of Paris in August 1944.\n\nAt the [[Yalta Conference]] it was agreed that membership would be open to nations that had joined the Allies by 1 March 1945.<ref>Robert C. Hilderbrand, ''Dumbarton Oaks: The Origins of the United Nations and the Search for Postwar Security'' (UNC Press, 2001)</ref> [[Brazil]], [[Syria]] and a number of other countries qualified for membership by declarations of war on either Germany or Japan in the first three months of 1945 \u2013 in some cases retroactively.\n\n===Founding the United Nations===\n{{Further|History of the United Nations}}\n\n==Establishment==\n[[File:UN charter logo.png|thumb|left|200px|Insignia of the Conference of San Francisco, prototype of the current logo of the United Nations]]\n[[File:United Nations Member States-1945.png|thumb|500px|The UN in 1945. In light blue, the founding members. In dark blue, protectorates and colonies of the founding members.]]\nOn 25 April 1945, the [[United Nations Conference on International Organization]] began in [[San Francisco]]. In addition to Governments, a number of [[non-governmental organizations|non-government organizations]], including [[Rotary International]] and [[Lions Clubs International]] received invitations to assist in the drafting of a charter. After working for two months, the fifty nations represented at the conference signed the [[United Nations Charter|Charter of the United Nations]] on 26 June.  [[Poland]], which was unable to send a representative to the conference due to political instability, signed the charter on 15 October 1945.  The charter stated that before it would come into effect, it must be ratified by the Governments of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]], [[France]], the [[Soviet Union|USSR]], the [[United Kingdom]], and the [[United States]], and by a majority of the other 46 signatories.  This occurred on 24&nbsp;October 1945, and the United Nations was officially formed.<ref>https://www.un.org/aboutun/sanfrancisco/history.html The 60th Anniversary of the San Francisco Conference</ref>\n\nThe date each founding member state deposited their ratification of the UN Charter is as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/depts/dhl/unms/founders.shtml|title=UN{{!}}DPI \u2014 OD{{!}}Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld Library: Member States{{!}}On the Record|last=Division|first=United Nations, Department of Public Information, Outreach|date=2009-09-28|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=}}</ref>\n* USA \u2013 8 Aug 1945\n* France \u2013 31 Aug 1945 \n* Dominican Rep. \u2013 4 Sep 1945 \n* Nicaragua \u2013 6 Sep 1945\n* New Zealand \u2013 19 Sep 1945\n* Brazil \u2013 21 Sep 1945\n* Argentina \u2013 24 Sep 1945\n* El Salvador \u2013 26 Sep 1945\n* Haiti \u2013 27 Sep 1945\n* China \u2013 28 Sep 1945\n* Turkey \u2013 28 Sep 1945\n* Denmark \u2013 9 October 1945\n* Chile \u2013 11 Oct 1945\n* Philippines \u2013 11 Oct 1945\n* Paraguay \u2013 12 Oct 1945\n* Cuba \u2013 15 Oct 1945\n* Lebanon \u2013 15 Oct 1945\n* Iran \u2013 16 Oct 1945\n* Luxembourg \u2013 17 Oct 1945\n* Saudi Arabia \u2013 18 Oct 1945\n* Czechoslovakia \u2013 19 Oct 1945\n* Syria \u2013 19 Oct 1945\n* Yugoslavia \u2013 19 Oct 1945\n* UK \u2013 20 Oct 1945\n* Egypt \u2013 22 Oct 1945\n* Byelorussia \u2013 24 Oct 1945\n* Poland \u2013 24 Oct 1945\n* Ukraine \u2013 24 Oct 1945\n* USSR \u2013 24 Oct 1945 (note - the United Nations was established on this date) \n* Greece \u2013 25 Oct 1945\n* India \u2013 30 Oct 1945\n* Peru \u2013 31 Oct 1945\n* Australia \u2013 1 Nov 1945\n* Costa Rica \u2013 2 Nov 1945\n* Liberia \u2013 2 Nov 1945\n* Colombia \u2013 5 Nov 1945\n* Mexico \u2013 7 Nov 1945\n* South Africa \u2013 7 Nov 1945\n* Canada \u2013 9 Nov 1945\n* Ethiopia \u2013 13 Nov 1945\n* Panama \u2013 13 Nov 1945\n* Bolivia \u2013 14 Nov 1945\n* Venezuela \u2013 15 Nov 1945\n* Honduras \u2013 17 Nov 1945\n* Guatemala \u2013 21 Nov 1945\n* Norway \u2013 27 Nov 1945\n* Netherlands \u2013 10 Dec 1945\n* Uruguay \u2013 18 Dec 1945\n* Ecuador \u2013 21 Dec 1945\n* Iraq \u2013 21 Dec 1945\n* Belgium \u2013 27 Dec 1945\n\n[[File:UN_Plaques.jpg|thumb|left|Plaques unveiled in 1996 to commemorate the first meeting of the General Assembly]]\nThe first meeting of the General Assembly was held in Westminster [[Methodist Central Hall Westminster|Central Hall]], [[London]], on 10 January 1946.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the United Nations 1941 - 1950 |url=https://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/1941-1950.shtml |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=12 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312020304/http://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/1941-1950.shtml |archivedate=12 March 2015 }}</ref> The Security Council met for the first time a week later in [[Church House, Westminster]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/sc/about/ |title=What is the Security Council? |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> The [[League of Nations]] formally dissolved itself on 18 April 1946 and transferred its mission to the United Nations.\n\n==Activities==\n{{See also|History of United Nations Peacekeeping}}\nThe United Nations has achieved considerable prominence in the social arena, fostering [[human rights]], [[economic development]], [[decolonization]], [[health]] and [[education]], for example, and interesting itself in [[refugee]]s and [[trade]].\n\nThe leaders of the UN had high hopes that it would act to prevent conflicts between nations and make future wars impossible. Those hopes have obviously not fully come to pass.  From about 1947 until 1991 the division of the world into hostile camps during the [[Cold War]] made agreement on [[peacekeeping]] matters extremely difficult. Following the end of the Cold War, renewed calls arose for the UN to become the agency for achieving world peace and co-operation, as several dozen active military conflicts continued to rage across the globe. The breakup of the Soviet Union has also left the [[United States]] in a unique position of global dominance, creating a variety of new problems for the UN (See the [[United States and the United Nations]]).\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:United Nations HQ - New York City.jpg|thumb|alt=Two skyscraper buildings on the bank of a river.|[[Headquarters of the United Nations|UN headquarters]] in [[City of New York|New York City]]]][[File:Vereinte Nationen in Wien.jpg|alt=Huge complex of skyscrapers and other large buildings interlaced with trees and gardens. The surrounding area as far as the horizon is filled with trees and large rivers. In the foreground a crane and small building site show that a new construction is underway.|thumb|UN building in [[Vienna]]]]\n\nIn June 1945, delegates from around the world gathered in San Francisco to draft the charter for the United Nations.<ref name=\"Philadelphia\">{{cite web |url=https://hiddencityphila.org/2018/11/when-the-united-nations-almost-chose-philly-for-its-hq/ |title=When the United Nations Almost Chose Philly For Its HQ |author=Historical Society of Philadelphia |work=Hidden City Philadelphia |date=November 23, 2018 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> Potential sites for the UN Headquarters included [[Vienna]], [[Switzerland]], [[Berlin]], [[Quebec]], and the [[Netherlands]] before the delegation decided on a headquarters in the United States by December 1945.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.niagara-gazette.com/opinion/columns/glynn-navy-island-eyed-as-home-for-the-u-n/article_9a5b10e4-7f5a-52c4-aae9-0fcf5be76a73.html |title=Glynn - Navy Island eyed as home for U.N. |author=Glynn, Don |work=Niagara Gazette |date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> Many U.S. cities vied for the honor of hosting the UN Headquarters site, such as [[Marin County, California]], [[St. Louis]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]], [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County, CT]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County, NY]], [[Flushing Meadows-Corona Park]] in [[Queens]], [[Tuskahoma, Oklahoma]], the [[Black Hills]] of [[South Dakota]], [[Belle Isle State Park (Michigan)|Belle Isle]] in [[Detroit]], and a site on [[Navy Island]] straddling the U.S.-Canada border were considered as potential sites for the UN Headquarters.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\">{{cite magazine |last=Atwater |first=Elton |date=April 1976 |title=Philadelphia's Quest to Become the Permanent Headquarters of the United Nations |jstor=20091055 |magazine=The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography |location=Pennsylvania |publisher=The Historical Society of Pennsylvania; University of Pennsylvania Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/04/02/detroits-quixotic-bid-to-host-the-united-nations/ |title=Detroit's Quixotic Bid to Host the United Nations |author=Mires, Charlene |work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=April 2, 2013 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> San Francisco, where the UN Headquarters delegation was held, was favored by [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[China]], and the [[Philippines]] due to the city's proximity to their countries.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> The UN and many of its delegates seriously considered [[Philadelphia]] for the headquarters; the city offered to donate land in several select sites, including [[Fairmount Park]], [[Andorra, Philadelphia|Andorra]], and a [[Center City, Philadelphia]] location which would have placed the headquarters along a [[esplanade|mall]] extending from [[Independence Hall]] to [[Penn's Landing]].<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/>\n\nIn 1946, [[John D. Rockefeller III]] and [[Laurance Rockefeller]] each offered their respective residences in [[Kykuit]] in [[Mount Pleasant, New York]] as headquarters for the UN, but the proposals were vetoed as the sites were too isolated from Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Estate offered as site for the UN headquarters |authors=Harr, John Ensor Harr & Johnson, Peter J. |work=The Rockefeller Century: Three Generations of America's Greatest Family|location= New York|publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons|year= 1988|pages=432\u201333}}</ref> The Soviet Union vetoed Boston due to the denunciations of [[Soviet]] expansion by [[John E. Swift]], a [[Massachusetts]] judge and [[Supreme Knight of the Knights of Columbus]].<ref name=\"Lapomarda\">{{cite book|title=The Knights of Columbus in Massachusetts|last=Lapomarda, S.J.|first=Vincent A.|publisher=Knights of Columbus Massachusetts State Council|year=1992|isbn=|edition=second|location=Norwood, Massachusetts|pages=41}}</ref>\n\nNew York City Planning Commissioner [[Robert Moses]] convinced [[Nelson Rockefeller]] to purchase a {{convert|17|and|18|acre|1}} piece of land along the [[East River]] in New York City from real estate developer [[William Zeckendorf]] Sr.;<ref name=\"NYTimes-UN-Ideas-2010\">{{cite news | last=Gray | first=Christopher | title=The U.N.: One Among Many Ideas for the Site | website=The New York Times | date=2010-04-25 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/realestate/25streets.html | access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>  The purchase was funded by Nelson's father, [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]] The Rockefeller family owned the [[Tudor City]] Apartments across First Avenue from the Zeckendorf site.<ref name=\"NYTimes-FYI-2003\">{{cite news |title=F.Y.I. |first=Ed Jr. |last=Boland |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/08/nyregion/fyi-015636.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=June 8, 2003 |accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> The UN ultimately chose the New York City site over Philadelphia after Rockefeller offered to donate the land along the East River.<ref name=\"Philadelphia\" /> The UN headquarters officially opened on January 9, 1951, although construction was not formally completed until October 9, 1952.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/10/10/archives/work-completed-on-u-n-buildings-68000000-plant-finished-lie.html|title=WORK COMPLETED ON U. N. BUILDINGS; $68,000,000 Plant Finished -- Lie Announces a Plan to Reorganize Top Staff WORK COMPLETED ON U. N. BUILDINGS|last=Hamilton|first=Thomas J.|date=1952-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and associated organizations==\n{{Expand section|date=January 2011}}\nThe basic constitutional makeup of the United Nations has changed little, though vastly increased membership has altered the functioning of some elements. The UN as a whole has generated a rich assortment of [[non-governmental organization]]s and special bodies over the years: some with a regional focus, some specific to the various [[peacekeeping]] missions, and others of global scope and importance. Other bodies (such as the [[International Labour Organization]]) formed prior to the establishment of the United Nations and only subsequently became associated with it.\n\n==Milestones==\n* In October 2015 over 350 landmarks in 60 countries were lit in blue to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the world body.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=52346#.ViwB1G5BnYs|title=World lights up in UN blue to mark Organization's milestone anniversary|publisher=UN News Centre|date=22 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/10/23/world/ap-un-united-nations-at-70.html|title=Over 200 Landmarks to Light Up UN Blue on 70th Anniversary|work=The New York Times|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/unicphoto/sets/72157657328013193|title=Turn the World #UNBlue|publisher=United Nations Information Centres|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n* [[Growth in United Nations membership]]\n* [[List of members of the United Nations Security Council]]\n* [[Timeline of UN peacekeeping missions]]\n* [[United Nations Secretary-General|List of UN Secretaries-General]]\n* [[Attacks on humanitarian workers]]\n* [[Reform of the United Nations]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Baehr, Peter R., and Leon Gordenker. ''The United Nations in the 1990s'' (St. Martin's Press, 1992)\n* Bellamy, Alex J., and Paul D. Williams, eds. ''Providing Peacekeepers: The Politics, Challenges, and Future of United Nations Peacekeeping Contributions'' (Oxford University Press, 2013)\n* Bergesen, Helge Ole, and Leiv Lunde. ''Dinosaurs or Dynamos: the United Nations and the World Bank at the turn of the century'' (Routledge, 2013)\n* Bosco, David L. ''Five to rule them all: the UN Security Council and the making of the modern world'' (Oxford University Press, 2009)\n* Clark, Ian, and Christian Reus-Smit. \"Liberal internationalism, the practice of special responsibilities and evolving politics of the security council.\" ''International Politics'' (2013) 50#1 pp: 38\u201356.\n* Dykmann, Klaas. \"On the Origins of the United Nations: When and How Did it Begin?.\" ''Journal of International Organizations Studies'' 3.1 (2012): 79\u201384.  [http://journal-iostudies.org/sites/journal-iostudies.org/files/JIOSfinal_9_0.pdf  online]\n* Ferdinand, Peter. \"Rising powers at the UN: an analysis of the voting behaviour of brics in the General Assembly.\" ''Third World Quarterly'' (2014) 35#3 pp: 376\u2013391.\n* Hanhim\u00e4ki, Jussi M. ''The United Nations: a very short introduction'' (Oxford University Press, 2015).\n* Hiscocks, Richard. ''The Security Council: A study in adolescence'' (Simon and Schuster, 1974)\n* Luck, Edward C. ''UN Security Council: practice and promise'' (Routledge, 2006)\n* Mazower, Mark.''No Enchanted Palace: The End of Empire and the Ideological Origins of the United Nations'' (Princeton UP, 2009),\n* Meisler, Stanley. ''United Nations: The First Fifty Years'' (1995) \n* Peters, Laurence. ''The United Nations: history and core ideas'' (Springer, 2016).\n* Plesch, Dan. ''America, Hitler and the UN: How the Allies Won World War II and Forged a Peace.'' (Bloomsbury Publishing, 2010); the wartime alliance called the \"United Nations\"\n* Rusell, Ruth B. ''A History of the United Nations Charter: The Role of the United States, 1940-1945'' (Washington: Brookings Institution, 1958.) \n* O'Sullivan, Christopher D. ''The United Nations: A Concise History''  (The Anvil Series, Krieger Publishing Company, 2005)\n* Phillips, Walter Ray. \"United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.\" ''Montana Law Review'' 24.1 (2014): 2.\n* Roberts, Adam, and Dominik Zaum. ''Selective security: war and the United Nations Security Council since 1945'' (Routledge, 2013)\n* Saltford, John. ''The United Nations and the Indonesian takeover of West Papua, 1962-1969: the anatomy of betrayal'' (Routledge, 2013)\n* Schlesinger, Stephen C. ''Act of creation: The founding of the United Nations: A story of superpowers, secret agents, wartime allies and enemies, and their quest for a peaceful world.'' (Westview Press, 2003).\n* Vreeland, James Raymond, and Axel Dreher. ''The Political Economy of the United Nations Security Council: Money and Influence'' (Cambridge University Press, 2014)\n* Weiss, Thomas G. ''What's Wrong with the United Nations and how to Fix it'' (John Wiley & Sons, 2013)\n* Wuthnow, Joel. ''Chinese diplomacy and the UN Security Council: beyond the veto'' (Routledge, 2012)\n\n===Primary sources===\n* Cordier, Andrew W., and Wilder Foote, eds. ''Public Papers of the Secretaries General of the United Nations'' (4 vol; Columbia University Press, 2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unhistory.org/ UN Intellectual History Project] \u2013 Academic study of UN history\n* [http://www.timedb.com/topic/united-nations United Nations Events Timeline]\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/paw/274.html Declaration by United Nations, January 1, 1942]\n* [http://www.unhistoryproject.org/ UN History Project] \u2013 Website providing resources, timelines, lectures, and bibliographies of UN history\n\n{{United Nations}}\n{{United Nations' relations with its Member States|state=autocollapse}}\n{{LN and UN Secretaries-General}}\n{{UN International Years}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The United Nations}}\n[[Category:History of the United Nations| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:United Nations member countries  world map.PNG|thumb|500px|alt=A map of the world with countries displayed in colours corresponding to the dates the countries joined the United Nations. Countries not involved with the United Nations are shown in grey.|A map of the world showing when countries joined the United Nations]][[File:UnitedNations.gif|thumb|alt=A black and white motion picture of some men signing papers on a desk in the center of a huge decorated room.|The founding of the [[United Nations]]]]\nThe '''history of the [[United Nations]]''' as an international organization has its origins in [[World War II]]. Since then its aims and activities have expanded to make it the archetypal <span lang=\"te\" dir=\"ltr\">international</span> body in the early 21st century.\n\n==Origins==\nThe earliest concrete plan for a new world organization to replace the ineffective [[League of Nations]] began under the aegis of the [[US State Department]] in 1939.<ref>Townsend Hoopes and Douglas Brinkley, ''FDR and the Creation of the U.N.'' (1997) pp 1-55</ref> On 12 June 1941, representatives of the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the Union of South Africa, and of the exiled governments of Belgium, Czechoslovakia, Greece, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, and Yugoslavia, as well as a representative of [[Charles de Gaulle|General de Gaulle]] of France, met in London and signed the Declaration of St. James's Palace. This was the first of six conferences that led up to the founding of the United Nations and the Charter of the United Nations.<ref>{{cite web|title=1941: The Declaration of St. James' Palace|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/history-united-nations-charter/1941-declaration-st-james-palace/index.html|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=28 March 2016|date=2015-08-25}}</ref>\n\nU.S. President [[Franklin Roosevelt]] first suggested using the name ''United Nations'', to refer to the [[Allies of World War II]], to British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] during the latter's [[Arcadia Conference|three-week visit]] to the White House in December 1941. Roosevelt suggested the name as an alternative to \"Associated Powers\", a term the U.S. used in the [[First World War]] (the U.S. was never formally a member of the [[Allies of World War I]] but entered the war in 1917 as a self-styled \"Associated Power\"). Churchill accepted the idea and cited [[Lord Byron]]'s use of the phrase \"United Nations\" in the poem ''[[Childe Harold's Pilgrimage]]'', which referred to the Allies at the [[Battle of Waterloo]] in 1815.<ref>{{cite web|title=United Nations|url=http://www.wordorigins.org/index.php/site/comments/united_nations/|website=Wordorigins.org|accessdate=28 March 2016|date=3 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ward|first1=Geoffrey C.|last2=Burns|first2=Ken|title=The Roosevelts: An Intimate History|date=2014|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0385353069|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=V73CAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=SA6-PA60#v=onepage&f=false|chapter=Nothing to Conceal}}</ref>\n\n===1942 \"Declaration of United Nations\"===\n[[File:United Nations \"Fight For Freedom\" poster.jpg|thumb|Poster for the founding of the United Nations]]\n{{main|Declaration by United Nations}}\nThe text of the \"Declaration of United Nations\" was drafted by U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, and Roosevelt aide [[Harry Hopkins]], while meeting at the White House on 29 December 1941. It incorporated Soviet suggestions, but left no role for France. The first official use of the term \"United Nations\" was on 1\u20132 January 1942 when 26 Governments signed the Declaration. One major change from the [[Atlantic Charter]] was the addition of a provision for religious freedom, which Stalin approved after Roosevelt insisted.<ref>David Roll, ''The Hopkins Touch: Harry Hopkins and the Forging of the Alliance to Defeat Hitler'' (2013) pp 172-75</ref><ref>Robert E. Sherwood, ''Roosevelt and Hopkins, An Intimate History'' (1948) pp 447-53</ref> By early 1945 it had been signed by 21 more states.<ref>{{cite book|author=Edmund Jan Osma\u0144czyk|title=Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements: T to Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6AB2CadyN7QC&pg=PA2445|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|page=2445|isbn=9780415939249}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nA JOINT DECLARATION BY THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, THE UNITED KINGDOM OF GREAT BRITAIN AND NORTHERN IRELAND, THE UNION OF SOVIET SOCIALIST REPUBLICS, CHINA, AUSTRALIA, BELGIUM, CANADA, COSTA RICA, CUBA, CZECHOSLOVAKIA, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC, EL SALVADOR, GREECE, GUATEMALA, HAITI, HONDURAS, INDIA, LUXEMBOURG, NETHERLANDS, NEW ZEALAND, NICARAGUA, NORWAY, PANAMA, POLAND, SOUTH AFRICA, YUGOSLAVIA\n<br />\nThe Governments signatory hereto,\n<br />\nHaving subscribed to a common program of purposes and principles embodied in the Joint Declaration of the President of the United States of America and the Prime Minister of Great Britain dated August 14, 1941, known as the Atlantic Charter,\n<br />\nBeing convinced that complete victory over their enemies is essential to defend life, liberty, independence and religious freedom, and to preserve human rights and justice in their own lands as well as in other lands, and that they are now engaged in a common struggle against savage and brutal forces seeking to subjugate the world,\n<br />\nDECLARE:\n<br />\n(1) Each Government pledges itself to employ its full resources, military or economic, against those members of the Tripartite Pact and its adherents with which such government is at war.\n<br />\n(2) Each Government pledges itself to cooperate with the Governments signatory hereto and not to make a separate armistice or peace with the enemies.\n<br />\nThe foregoing declaration may be adhered to by other nations which are, or which may be, rendering material assistance and contributions in the struggle for victory over Hitlerism.<ref>Text from [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/wwii/washc014.asp \"The Washington Conference 1941-1942\"]</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nDuring the war, the United Nations became the official term for the Allies. To join countries had to sign the Declaration and declare war on the Axis.<ref>Stephen C. Schlesinger, ''Act of creation: The founding of the United Nations: A story of superpowers, secret agents, wartime allies and enemies, and their quest for a peaceful world'' (2003)</ref>\n\n===Planning===\n[[File:Early United Nations official's passport from WW2 - working for UNRRA 1944.jpg|thumb|Early United Nations official's passport from World War Two - working for UNRRA, issued in 1944 for the Middle East]]\n[[Foreign policy of the Franklin D. Roosevelt administration|US President Franklin D. Roosevelt]] considered his most important legacy the creation of the United Nations, making a permanent organization  out of the wartime Alliance of the same name. He was the chief promoter of the United Nations idea. The first plans for the future international organization emerged in declarations signed at the wartime Allied conferences: the [[Moscow Conference (1943)|Moscow Conference]] and the [[Tehran Conference]] on 30 October 1943.\n\nRoosevelt had been a strong supporter of the League of Nations back in 1919\u201320, but was determined to avoid the mistakes Woodrow Wilson had made. The United Nations was FDR's highest postwar priority. He insisted on full coordination with the Republican leadership. He made sure that leading Republicans were on board, especially Senators [[Arthur Vandenberg]] of Michigan,<ref>James A. Gazell, \"Arthur H. Vandenberg, Internationalism, and the United Nations.\" ''Political Science Quarterly'' 88#3 (1973): 375-394. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2148990 online]</ref> and [[Warren Austin]] of Vermont.<ref>George T. Mazuzan. ''Warren R. Austin at the U. N., 1946-1953'' (Kent State UP, 1977).</ref> In a broad sense, Roosevelt believed that the UN could solve the minor problems and provide the chief mechanism to resolve any major Issues that arose among the great powers, all of whom had a veto. For FDR creating the UN was the most important goal for the entire war effort.<ref>For FDR,  \"establishing the United nations organization was the overarching strategic goal, the absolute first priority.\" {{cite book|author1=Townsend Hoopes|author2=Douglas Brinkley|title=FDR and the Creation of the U.N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OztJcfbnpDsC&pg=PA178|year=1997|publisher=Yale UP|page=178}}</ref> Roosevelt was especially interested in  international protection of human right, and in this area his wife played a major role as well.<ref>Ivy P. Urdang,  \"Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt: Human Rights and the Creation of the United Nations.\" ''OAH Magazine of History'' 22.2 (2008): 28-31.</ref><ref>M. Glen Johnson,  \"The contributions of Eleanor and Franklin Roosevelt to the development of international protection for human rights.\" '' Human Rights Quarterly'' 9 (1987): 19+.</ref>\n\nThe Allies had agreed to the basic structure of the new body at the [[Dumbarton Oaks Conference]] in 1944.<ref>Hoopes and Brinkley, ''FDR and the Creation of the U. N.'' (1997) pp 148-58.</ref> At Yalta, Roosevelt, Churchill, and Stalin agreed to the establishment of the United Nations, as well as the structure of the [[United Nations Security Council]].  Stalin insisted on having a veto and FDR finally agreed.  The participants at Yalta also agreed that the United Nations would convene for the first time in [[San Francisco]] in April 1945 in the [[United Nations Conference on International Organization]].  Roosevelt considered the United Nations to be his most important legacy. He provided continuous backstage political support at home and with Churchill and Stalin abroad. The Big Four of the United States, Britain, Soviet Union and China would make the major decisions, with France added later to provide permanent members of the all-powerful Security Council. Each had a veto power, thus avoiding the fatal weakness of the League of Nations, which had theoretically been able to order its members to act in defiance of their own parliaments.<ref>John Allphin Moore Jr. and Jerry Pubantz, ''To Create a New World?: American Presidents & the United Nations'' (1999), pp 27-79.</ref>\n \nRoosevelt went public with strong advocacy in the 1944 presidential campaign, and turned detailed planning over to the State Department, where [[Sumner Welles]] and Secretary [[Cordell Hull]] worked on the project. It was his ideas that \"four policemen\" would collaborate to keep and enforce the peace.  The United States, Britain, Soviet Union and China made the major decisions and became permanent members of the all-powerful Security Council; France was added to make five policemen.<ref>Stephen Schlesinger,  \"FDR's five policemen: creating the United Nations.\" ''World Policy Journal'' 11.3 (1994): 88-93. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/40209368 online]</ref>  Stalin insisted on a veto power. Roosevelt finally agreed, thus avoiding the fatal weakness of the League of Nations, which theoretically could order its members to act in defiance of their own parliaments.<ref>Townsend Hoopes and Douglas Brinkley, ''FDR and the Creation of the U. N.'' (1997)</ref>\n \nFrom 21 September to 7 October 1944, representatives of the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]], Britain, the US and the [[Soviet Union|USSR]]  met to elaborate plans at the [[Dumbarton Oaks Conference]] in Washington, D.C. Those and later talks produced proposals outlining the purposes of the United Nations organization, its membership and organs, as well as arrangements to maintain international peace and security and international economic and social cooperation. Governments and private citizens worldwide discussed and debated these proposals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/dumbarton_yalta.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016124053/http://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/dumbarton_yalta.shtml |archive-date=2015-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Winston Churchill urged Roosevelt to restore France to its status of a major Power after the liberation of Paris in August 1944.\n\nAt the [[Yalta Conference]] it was agreed that membership would be open to nations that had joined the Allies by 1 March 1945.<ref>Robert C. Hilderbrand, ''Dumbarton Oaks: The Origins of the United Nations and the Search for Postwar Security'' (UNC Press, 2001)</ref> [[Brazil]], [[Syria]] and a number of other countries qualified for membership by declarations of war on either Germany or Japan in the first three months of 1945 \u2013 in some cases retroactively.\n\n===Founding the United Nations===\n{{Further|History of the United Nations}}\n\n==Establishment==\n[[File:UN charter logo.png|thumb|left|200px|Insignia of the Conference of San Francisco, prototype of the current logo of the United Nations]]\n[[File:United Nations Member States-1945.png|thumb|500px|The UN in 1945. In light blue, the founding members. In dark blue, protectorates and colonies of the founding members.]]\nOn 25 April 1945, the [[United Nations Conference on International Organization]] began in [[San Francisco]]. In addition to Governments, a number of [[non-governmental organizations|non-government organizations]], including [[Rotary International]] and [[Lions Clubs International]] received invitations to assist in the drafting of a charter. After working for two months, the fifty nations represented at the conference signed the [[United Nations Charter|Charter of the United Nations]] on 26 June.  [[Poland]], which was unable to send a representative to the conference due to political instability, signed the charter on 15 October 1945.  The charter stated that before it would come into effect, it must be ratified by the Governments of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]], [[France]], the [[Soviet Union|USSR]], the [[United Kingdom]], and the [[United States]], and by a majority of the other 46 signatories.  This occurred on 24&nbsp;October 1945, and the United Nations was officially formed.<ref>https://www.un.org/aboutun/sanfrancisco/history.html The 60th Anniversary of the San Francisco Conference</ref>\n\nThe date each founding member state deposited their ratification of the UN Charter is as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/depts/dhl/unms/founders.shtml|title=UN{{!}}DPI \u2014 OD{{!}}Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld Library: Member States{{!}}On the Record|last=Division|first=United Nations, Department of Public Information, Outreach|date=2009-09-28|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=}}</ref>\n* USA \u2013 8 Aug 1945\n* France \u2013 31 Aug 1945 \n* Dominican Rep. \u2013 4 Sep 1945 \n* Nicaragua \u2013 6 Sep 1945\n* New Zealand \u2013 19 Sep 1945\n* Brazil \u2013 21 Sep 1945\n* Argentina \u2013 24 Sep 1945\n* El Salvador \u2013 26 Sep 1945\n* Haiti \u2013 27 Sep 1945\n* China \u2013 28 Sep 1945\n* Turkey \u2013 28 Sep 1945\n* Denmark \u2013 9 October 1945\n* Chile \u2013 11 Oct 1945\n* Philippines \u2013 11 Oct 1945\n* Paraguay \u2013 12 Oct 1945\n* Cuba \u2013 15 Oct 1945\n* Lebanon \u2013 15 Oct 1945\n* Iran \u2013 16 Oct 1945\n* Luxembourg \u2013 17 Oct 1945\n* Saudi Arabia \u2013 18 Oct 1945\n* Czechoslovakia \u2013 19 Oct 1945\n* Syria \u2013 19 Oct 1945\n* Yugoslavia \u2013 19 Oct 1945\n* UK \u2013 20 Oct 1945\n* Egypt \u2013 22 Oct 1945\n* Byelorussia \u2013 24 Oct 1945\n* Poland \u2013 24 Oct 1945\n* Ukraine \u2013 24 Oct 1945\n* USSR \u2013 24 Oct 1945 (note - the United Nations was established on this date) \n* Greece \u2013 25 Oct 1945\n* India \u2013 30 Oct 1945\n* Peru \u2013 31 Oct 1945\n* Australia \u2013 1 Nov 1945\n* Costa Rica \u2013 2 Nov 1945\n* Liberia \u2013 2 Nov 1945\n* Colombia \u2013 5 Nov 1945\n* Mexico \u2013 7 Nov 1945\n* South Africa \u2013 7 Nov 1945\n* Canada \u2013 9 Nov 1945\n* Ethiopia \u2013 13 Nov 1945\n* Panama \u2013 13 Nov 1945\n* Bolivia \u2013 14 Nov 1945\n* Venezuela \u2013 15 Nov 1945\n* Honduras \u2013 17 Nov 1945\n* Guatemala \u2013 21 Nov 1945\n* Norway \u2013 27 Nov 1945\n* Netherlands \u2013 10 Dec 1945\n* Uruguay \u2013 18 Dec 1945\n* Ecuador \u2013 21 Dec 1945\n* Iraq \u2013 21 Dec 1945\n* Belgium \u2013 27 Dec 1945\n\n[[File:UN_Plaques.jpg|thumb|left|Plaques unveiled in 1996 to commemorate the first meeting of the General Assembly]]\nThe first meeting of the General Assembly was held in Westminster [[Methodist Central Hall Westminster|Central Hall]], [[London]], on 10 January 1946.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the United Nations 1941 - 1950 |url=https://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/1941-1950.shtml |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=12 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312020304/http://www.un.org/en/aboutun/history/1941-1950.shtml |archivedate=12 March 2015 }}</ref> The Security Council met for the first time a week later in [[Church House, Westminster]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/sc/about/ |title=What is the Security Council? |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> The [[League of Nations]] formally dissolved itself on 18 April 1946 and transferred its mission to the United Nations.\n\n==Activities==\n{{See also|History of United Nations Peacekeeping}}\nThe United Nations has achieved considerable prominence in the social arena, fostering [[human rights]], [[economic development]], [[decolonization]], [[health]] and [[education]], for example, and interesting itself in [[refugee]]s and [[trade]].\n\nThe leaders of the UN had high hopes that it would act to prevent conflicts between nations and make future wars impossible. Those hopes have obviously not fully come to pass.  From about 1947 until 1991 the division of the world into hostile camps during the [[Cold War]] made agreement on [[peacekeeping]] matters extremely difficult. Following the end of the Cold War, renewed calls arose for the UN to become the agency for achieving world peace and co-operation, as several dozen active military conflicts continued to rage across the globe. The breakup of the Soviet Union has also left the [[United States]] in a unique position of global dominance, creating a variety of new problems for the UN (See the [[United States and the United Nations]]).\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:United Nations HQ - New York City.jpg|thumb|alt=Two skyscraper buildings on the bank of a river.|[[Headquarters of the United Nations|UN headquarters]] in [[City of New York|New York City]]]][[File:Vereinte Nationen in Wien.jpg|alt=Huge complex of skyscrapers and other large buildings interlaced with trees and gardens. The surrounding area as far as the horizon is filled with trees and large rivers. In the foreground a crane and small building site show that a new construction is underway.|thumb|UN building in [[Vienna]]]]\n\nIn June 1945, delegates from around the world gathered in San Francisco to draft the charter for the United Nations.<ref name=\"Philadelphia\">{{cite web |url=https://hiddencityphila.org/2018/11/when-the-united-nations-almost-chose-philly-for-its-hq/ |title=When the United Nations Almost Chose Philly For Its HQ |author=Historical Society of Philadelphia |work=Hidden City Philadelphia |date=November 23, 2018 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> Potential sites for the UN Headquarters included [[Vienna]], [[Switzerland]], [[Berlin]], [[Quebec]], and the [[Netherlands]] before the delegation decided on a headquarters in the United States by December 1945.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.niagara-gazette.com/opinion/columns/glynn-navy-island-eyed-as-home-for-the-u-n/article_9a5b10e4-7f5a-52c4-aae9-0fcf5be76a73.html |title=Glynn - Navy Island eyed as home for U.N. |author=Glynn, Don |work=Niagara Gazette |date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> Many U.S. cities vied for the honor of hosting the UN Headquarters site, such as [[Marin County, California]], [[St. Louis]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]], [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County, CT]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County, NY]], [[Flushing Meadows-Corona Park]] in [[Queens]], [[Tuskahoma, Oklahoma]], the [[Black Hills]] of [[South Dakota]], [[Belle Isle State Park (Michigan)|Belle Isle]] in [[Detroit]], and a site on [[Navy Island]] straddling the U.S.-Canada border were considered as potential sites for the UN Headquarters.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\">{{cite magazine |last=Atwater |first=Elton |date=April 1976 |title=Philadelphia's Quest to Become the Permanent Headquarters of the United Nations |jstor=20091055 |magazine=The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography |location=Pennsylvania |publisher=The Historical Society of Pennsylvania; University of Pennsylvania Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/04/02/detroits-quixotic-bid-to-host-the-united-nations/ |title=Detroit's Quixotic Bid to Host the United Nations |author=Mires, Charlene |work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=April 2, 2013 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> San Francisco, where the UN Headquarters delegation was held, was favored by [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[China]], and the [[Philippines]] due to the city's proximity to their countries.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> The UN and many of its delegates seriously considered [[Philadelphia]] for the headquarters; the city offered to donate land in several select sites, including [[Fairmount Park]], [[Andorra, Philadelphia|Andorra]], and a [[Center City, Philadelphia]] location which would have placed the headquarters along a [[esplanade|mall]] extending from [[Independence Hall]] to [[Penn's Landing]].<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/>\n\nIn 1946, [[John D. Rockefeller III]] and [[Laurance Rockefeller]] each offered their respective residences in [[Kykuit]] in [[Mount Pleasant, New York]] as headquarters for the UN, but the proposals were vetoed as the sites were too isolated from Manhattan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Estate offered as site for the UN headquarters |authors=Harr, John Ensor Harr & Johnson, Peter J. |work=The Rockefeller Century: Three Generations of America's Greatest Family|location= New York|publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons|year= 1988|pages=432\u201333}}</ref> The Soviet Union vetoed Boston due to the denunciations of [[Soviet]] expansion by [[John E. Swift]], a [[Massachusetts]] judge and [[Supreme Knight of the Knights of Columbus]].<ref name=\"Lapomarda\">{{cite book|title=The Knights of Columbus in Massachusetts|last=Lapomarda, S.J.|first=Vincent A.|publisher=Knights of Columbus Massachusetts State Council|year=1992|isbn=|edition=second|location=Norwood, Massachusetts|pages=41}}</ref>\n\nNew York City Planning Commissioner [[Robert Moses]] convinced [[Nelson Rockefeller]] to purchase a {{convert|17|and|18|acre|1}} piece of land along the [[East River]] in New York City from real estate developer [[William Zeckendorf]] Sr.;<ref name=\"NYTimes-UN-Ideas-2010\">{{cite news | last=Gray | first=Christopher | title=The U.N.: One Among Many Ideas for the Site | website=The New York Times | date=2010-04-25 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/realestate/25streets.html | access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>  The purchase was funded by Nelson's father, [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]] The Rockefeller family owned the [[Tudor City]] Apartments across First Avenue from the Zeckendorf site.<ref name=\"NYTimes-FYI-2003\">{{cite news |title=F.Y.I. |first=Ed Jr. |last=Boland |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/08/nyregion/fyi-015636.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=June 8, 2003 |accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> The UN ultimately chose the New York City site over Philadelphia after Rockefeller offered to donate the land along the East River.<ref name=\"Philadelphia\" /> The UN headquarters officially opened on January 9, 1951, although construction was not formally completed until October 9, 1952.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/10/10/archives/work-completed-on-u-n-buildings-68000000-plant-finished-lie.html|title=WORK COMPLETED ON U. N. BUILDINGS; $68,000,000 Plant Finished -- Lie Announces a Plan to Reorganize Top Staff WORK COMPLETED ON U. N. BUILDINGS|last=Hamilton|first=Thomas J.|date=1952-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and associated organizations==\n{{Expand section|date=January 2011}}\nThe basic constitutional makeup of the United Nations has changed little, though vastly increased membership has altered the functioning of some elements. The UN as a whole has generated a rich assortment of [[non-governmental organization]]s and special bodies over the years: some with a regional focus, some specific to the various [[peacekeeping]] missions, and others of global scope and importance. Other bodies (such as the [[International Labour Organization]]) formed prior to the establishment of the United Nations and only subsequently became associated with it.\n\n==Milestones==\n* In October 2015 over 350 landmarks in 60 countries were lit in blue to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the world body.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=52346#.ViwB1G5BnYs|title=World lights up in UN blue to mark Organization's milestone anniversary|publisher=UN News Centre|date=22 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/10/23/world/ap-un-united-nations-at-70.html|title=Over 200 Landmarks to Light Up UN Blue on 70th Anniversary|work=The New York Times|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/unicphoto/sets/72157657328013193|title=Turn the World #UNBlue|publisher=United Nations Information Centres|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n* [[Growth in United Nations membership]]\n* [[List of members of the United Nations Security Council]]\n* [[Timeline of UN peacekeeping missions]]\n* [[United Nations Secretary-General|List of UN Secretaries-General]]\n* [[Attacks on humanitarian workers]]\n* [[Reform of the United Nations]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Baehr, Peter R., and Leon Gordenker. ''The United Nations in the 1990s'' (St. Martin's Press, 1992)\n* Bellamy, Alex J., and Paul D. Williams, eds. ''Providing Peacekeepers: The Politics, Challenges, and Future of United Nations Peacekeeping Contributions'' (Oxford University Press, 2013)\n* Bergesen, Helge Ole, and Leiv Lunde. ''Dinosaurs or Dynamos: the United Nations and the World Bank at the turn of the century'' (Routledge, 2013)\n* Bosco, David L. ''Five to rule them all: the UN Security Council and the making of the modern world'' (Oxford University Press, 2009)\n* Clark, Ian, and Christian Reus-Smit. \"Liberal internationalism, the practice of special responsibilities and evolving politics of the security council.\" ''International Politics'' (2013) 50#1 pp: 38\u201356.\n* Dykmann, Klaas. \"On the Origins of the United Nations: When and How Did it Begin?.\" ''Journal of International Organizations Studies'' 3.1 (2012): 79\u201384.  [http://journal-iostudies.org/sites/journal-iostudies.org/files/JIOSfinal_9_0.pdf  online]\n* Ferdinand, Peter. \"Rising powers at the UN: an analysis of the voting behaviour of brics in the General Assembly.\" ''Third World Quarterly'' (2014) 35#3 pp: 376\u2013391.\n* Hanhim\u00e4ki, Jussi M. ''The United Nations: a very short introduction'' (Oxford University Press, 2015).\n* Hiscocks, Richard. ''The Security Council: A study in adolescence'' (Simon and Schuster, 1974)\n* Luck, Edward C. ''UN Security Council: practice and promise'' (Routledge, 2006)\n* Mazower, Mark.''No Enchanted Palace: The End of Empire and the Ideological Origins of the United Nations'' (Princeton UP, 2009),\n* Meisler, Stanley. ''United Nations: The First Fifty Years'' (1995) \n* Peters, Laurence. ''The United Nations: history and core ideas'' (Springer, 2016).\n* Plesch, Dan. ''America, Hitler and the UN: How the Allies Won World War II and Forged a Peace.'' (Bloomsbury Publishing, 2010); the wartime alliance called the \"United Nations\"\n* Rusell, Ruth B. ''A History of the United Nations Charter: The Role of the United States, 1940-1945'' (Washington: Brookings Institution, 1958.) \n* O'Sullivan, Christopher D. ''The United Nations: A Concise History''  (The Anvil Series, Krieger Publishing Company, 2005)\n* Phillips, Walter Ray. \"United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.\" ''Montana Law Review'' 24.1 (2014): 2.\n* Roberts, Adam, and Dominik Zaum. ''Selective security: war and the United Nations Security Council since 1945'' (Routledge, 2013)\n* Saltford, John. ''The United Nations and the Indonesian takeover of West Papua, 1962-1969: the anatomy of betrayal'' (Routledge, 2013)\n* Schlesinger, Stephen C. ''Act of creation: The founding of the United Nations: A story of superpowers, secret agents, wartime allies and enemies, and their quest for a peaceful world.'' (Westview Press, 2003).\n* Vreeland, James Raymond, and Axel Dreher. ''The Political Economy of the United Nations Security Council: Money and Influence'' (Cambridge University Press, 2014)\n* Weiss, Thomas G. ''What's Wrong with the United Nations and how to Fix it'' (John Wiley & Sons, 2013)\n* Wuthnow, Joel. ''Chinese diplomacy and the UN Security Council: beyond the veto'' (Routledge, 2012)\n\n===Primary sources===\n* Cordier, Andrew W., and Wilder Foote, eds. ''Public Papers of the Secretaries General of the United Nations'' (4 vol; Columbia University Press, 2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unhistory.org/ UN Intellectual History Project] \u2013 Academic study of UN history\n* [http://www.timedb.com/topic/united-nations United Nations Events Timeline]\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/paw/274.html Declaration by United Nations, January 1, 1942]\n* [http://www.unhistoryproject.org/ UN History Project] \u2013 Website providing resources, timelines, lectures, and bibliographies of UN history\n\n{{United Nations}}\n{{United Nations' relations with its Member States|state=autocollapse}}\n{{LN and UN Secretaries-General}}\n{{UN International Years}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The United Nations}}\n[[Category:History of the United Nations| ]]\n", "name_user": "120.59.20.146", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOrigins)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_United_Nations"}
{"title_page": "Anne Holmlund", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix= \n|name            = Anne Holmlund\n|honorific-suffix= \n|image           = Anne Holmlund.jpg\n|caption         = \n|office          = [[Minister of the Interior (Finland)|Minister of the Interior]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/v9l/16 |title=Council of State - Ministers of Interior |publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=27 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|term_start      = 19 April 2007\n|term_end        = 22 June 2011\n|president       = [[Tarja Halonen]]\n|primeminister   = [[Matti Vanhanen]]<br>[[Mari Kiviniemi]]\n|predecessor     = Olli-Pekka Heinonen\n|successor       = [[P\u00e4ivi R\u00e4s\u00e4nen]]\n|office2         = Member of the [[Parliament of Finland]]\n|constituency2   = [[Satakunta (constituency)|Satakunta]]\n|majority2       = \n|term_start2     = February 02, 2002\n|term_end2    = \n|predecessor2 = \n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1964|04|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Pori]], Finland\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname    = Anne Elisabeth Holmlund\n|nationality  = Finnish\n|party        = [[National Coalition Party]]\n|spouse       = Jarmo Peltomaa\n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = [[Ulvila]]\n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = Politician\n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\n\n'''Anne Elisabeth Holmlund''' (born April 18, 1964) is a [[Politics of Finland|Finnish]] [[politician]] and [[Minister of the Interior (Finland)|Minister of the Interior]] of Finland from 2007 to 2011. She has been a Member of Parliament for the [[National Coalition Party]] since 2002.\n\n==Political career==\nHolmlund has been a member of the [[city council]] of [[Ulvila]] since 1989, and the council chairman 2001-2002 and 2005\u20132007. She was a member of the [[Kommunstyrelse|kaupunginhallitus]] 1993-2000 and the vice-chairman 2003\u20132004. She has been a Member of Parliament for the [[National Coalition Party]] since 2002. On April 19, 2007 she was chosen to be Interior Minister in [[Matti Vanhanen's second cabinet]].<ref name=\"eduskunta\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hex5000.sh?kieli=en&${APPL}=hetekaue_en&${BASE}=hetekaue_en&${THWIDS}=12.37/1233673237_65685&${oohtml}=hex/hex3500&${html}=hex/hex3500&${snhtml}=hex/hexnosyn_en&${savehtml}=/thwfakta/hetekau/hex/hex3000_en.shtml&tyyppi=hakusetti |title=Parliament of Finland - Anne Holmlund information page |accessdate=2009-02-03 |publisher=[[Parliament of Finland]] |date=2008-09-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611035527/http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hex5000.sh?kieli=en&%24%7BAPPL%7D=hetekaue_en&%24%7BBASE%7D=hetekaue_en&%24%7BTHWIDS%7D=12.37%2F1233673237_65685&%24%7Boohtml%7D=hex%2Fhex3500&%24%7Bhtml%7D=hex%2Fhex3500&%24%7Bsnhtml%7D=hex%2Fhexnosyn_en&%24%7Bsavehtml%7D=%2Fthwfakta%2Fhetekau%2Fhex%2Fhex3000_en.shtml&tyyppi=hakusetti |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Kauhajoki school shooting]] in September 2008 Holmlund came under considerable pressure from some members of parliament, particularly those in the [[Left Alliance (Finland)|Left Alliance]],<ref name=\"Stand-by-minister\" /> to quit for failing to change legislation in order to prevent the shooting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20080924-finns-face-hard-questions-saari-killing-shooting-guns-finland |title=Finns face tough questions after killing spree |accessdate=2009-02-10 |work= |publisher=[[France 24]] |date=2008-09-24}}</ref> A [[Jokela school shooting|similar event in Jokela]] had taken place barely a year earlier. Leading the call for her deposition was Anneli Lapintie; [[Tarja Filatov]], parliamentary group leader of the [[Opposition (parliamentary)|opposition]] [[Social Democratic Party of Finland]] (SDP) also questioned the government over what it had done since the Jokela incident.<ref name=\"Minister-resign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Calls+for+Interior+Minister+to+resign+Katainen+backs+Holmlund/1135239762534|title=Calls for Interior Minister to resign; Katainen backs Holmlund|publisher=[[Helsingin Sanomat]]|date=2008-09-26|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Jyrki Katainen]] issued his full support to Holmlund.<ref name=\"Minister-resign\" /> A survey by pollster Taloustutkimus for [[YLE]] showed that dissension towards Holmlund was not widespread: only a quarter of members from smaller parties felt she should step down, only 10% of SDP members (with 80% supporting her to stay on), and 90% of the government's partners wanted her to hold on to her ministry. Amongst the population, 82% felt she should continue.<ref name=\"Stand-by-minister\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yle.fi/news/id102795.html|title=Majority of Finns Stand Behind Interior Minister Holmlund|publisher=[[YLE|YLE News]]|date=2008-09-26|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> Holmlund herself stated at a news conference that resignation \"would be tantamount to desertion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.helsinkitimes.fi/htimes/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3305&catid=24&Itemid=204 |title=Finnish interior minister says will not resign |accessdate=2009-02-10 |work= |publisher=[[Helsinki Times]] |date=2008-09-25 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHolmlund is married to Jarmo Peltomaa, and her father was Ilmari Holmlund, a known politician from Pori.<ref name=\"eduskunta\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20090323015734/http://www2.eduskunta.fi:80/fakta/edustaja/630/index.html}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holmlund, Anne}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pori]]\n[[Category:National Coalition Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Interior of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1999\u20132003)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2003\u201307)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2007\u201311)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2011\u201315)]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Finnish women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix= \n|name            = Anne Holmlund\n|honorific-suffix= \n|image           = Anne Holmlund.jpg\n|caption         = \n|office          = [[Minister of the Interior (Finland)|Minister of the Interior]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/v9l/16 |title=Council of State - Ministers of Interior |publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=27 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|term_start      = 19 April 2007\n|term_end        = 22 June 2011\n|president       = [[Tarja Halonen]]\n|primeminister   = [[Matti Vanhanen]]<br>[[Mari Kiviniemi]]\n|predecessor     = Olli-Pekka Heinonen\n|successor       = [[P\u00e4ivi R\u00e4s\u00e4nen]]\n|office2         = Member of the [[Parliament of Finland]]\n|constituency2   = [[Satakunta (constituency)|Satakunta]]\n|majority2       = \n|term_start2     = February 02, 2002\n|term_end2    = \n|predecessor2 = \n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1964|04|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Pori]], Finland\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname    = Anne Elisabeth Holmlund\n|nationality  = Finnish\n|party        = [[National Coalition Party]]\n|spouse       = Jarmo Peltomaa\n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = [[Ulvila]]\n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = Politician\n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\n\n'''Anne Elisabeth Holmlund''' (born April 18, 1964) is a [[Politics of Finland|Finnish]] [[politician]] and [[Minister of the Interior (Finland)|Minister of the Interior]] of Finland from 2007 to 2011. She has been a Member of Parliament for the [[National Coalition Party]] since 2002.\n\n==Political career==\nHolmlund has been a member of the [[city council]] of [[Ulvila]] since 1989, and the council chairman 2001-2002 and 2005-2007. She was a member of the [[Kommunstyrelse|kaupunginhallitus]] 1993-2000 and the vice-chairman 2003-2004. She has been a Member of Parliament for the [[National Coalition Party]] since 2002. On April 19, 2007 she was chosen to be Interior Minister in [[Matti Vanhanen's second cabinet]].<ref name=\"eduskunta\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hex5000.sh?kieli=en&${APPL}=hetekaue_en&${BASE}=hetekaue_en&${THWIDS}=12.37/1233673237_65685&${oohtml}=hex/hex3500&${html}=hex/hex3500&${snhtml}=hex/hexnosyn_en&${savehtml}=/thwfakta/hetekau/hex/hex3000_en.shtml&tyyppi=hakusetti |title=Parliament of Finland - Anne Holmlund information page |accessdate=2009-02-03 |publisher=[[Parliament of Finland]] |date=2008-09-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611035527/http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hex5000.sh?kieli=en&%24%7BAPPL%7D=hetekaue_en&%24%7BBASE%7D=hetekaue_en&%24%7BTHWIDS%7D=12.37%2F1233673237_65685&%24%7Boohtml%7D=hex%2Fhex3500&%24%7Bhtml%7D=hex%2Fhex3500&%24%7Bsnhtml%7D=hex%2Fhexnosyn_en&%24%7Bsavehtml%7D=%2Fthwfakta%2Fhetekau%2Fhex%2Fhex3000_en.shtml&tyyppi=hakusetti |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Kauhajoki school shooting]] in September 2008 Holmlund came under considerable pressure from some members of parliament, particularly those in the [[Left Alliance (Finland)|Left Alliance]],<ref name=\"Stand-by-minister\" /> to quit for failing to change legislation in order to prevent the shooting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20080924-finns-face-hard-questions-saari-killing-shooting-guns-finland |title=Finns face tough questions after killing spree |accessdate=2009-02-10 |work= |publisher=[[France 24]] |date=2008-09-24}}</ref> A [[Jokela school shooting|similar event in Jokela]] had taken place barely a year earlier. Leading the call for her deposition was Anneli Lapintie; [[Tarja Filatov]], parliamentary group leader of the [[Opposition (parliamentary)|opposition]] [[Social Democratic Party of Finland]] (SDP) also questioned the government over what it had done since the Jokela incident.<ref name=\"Minister-resign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Calls+for+Interior+Minister+to+resign+Katainen+backs+Holmlund/1135239762534|title=Calls for Interior Minister to resign; Katainen backs Holmlund|publisher=[[Helsingin Sanomat]]|date=2008-09-26|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Jyrki Katainen]] issued his full support to Holmlund.<ref name=\"Minister-resign\" /> A survey by pollster Taloustutkimus for [[YLE]] showed that dissension towards Holmlund was not widespread: only a quarter of members from smaller parties felt she should step down, only 10% of SDP members (with 80% supporting her to stay on), and 90% of the government's partners wanted her to hold on to her ministry. Amongst the population, 82% felt she should continue.<ref name=\"Stand-by-minister\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yle.fi/news/id102795.html|title=Majority of Finns Stand Behind Interior Minister Holmlund|publisher=[[YLE|YLE News]]|date=2008-09-26|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> Holmlund herself stated at a news conference that resignation \"would be tantamount to desertion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.helsinkitimes.fi/htimes/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3305&catid=24&Itemid=204 |title=Finnish interior minister says will not resign |accessdate=2009-02-10 |work= |publisher=[[Helsinki Times]] |date=2008-09-25 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHolmlund is married to Jarmo Peltomaa, and her father was Ilmari Holmlund, a known politician from Pori.<ref name=\"eduskunta\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20090323015734/http://www2.eduskunta.fi:80/fakta/edustaja/630/index.html}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holmlund, Anne}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pori]]\n[[Category:National Coalition Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Interior of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1999\u20132003)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2003\u201307)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2007\u201311)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2011\u201315)]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Finnish women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2005-2007 \u2192 2005\u20132007 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Holmlund"}
{"title_page": "List of botanical gardens in Malaysia", "text_new": "'''Botanical gardens in Malaysia''' have collections consisting entirely of Malaysia native and [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species; most have a collection that include plants from around the world. There are botanical gardens and [[Arboretum|arboreta]] in all states and territories of Malaysia, most are administered by local governments, some are privately owned.\n* Cameron Highlands Botanical Park, [[Cameron Highlands]]\n* Labuan Botanical Garden, [[Labuan Territory|Labuan]]\n* [[Malacca Botanical Garden]], [[Malacca]]\n* [[Penang Botanic Gardens]], [[Penang]]\n* Kuching Aquarium and Botanical Garden, [[Kuching]]\n* [[Putrajaya Botanical Garden]], [[Putrajaya]]\n* [[Perdana Botanical Gardens]], [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n* [[Rimba Ilmu Botanical Gardens]], [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n* Taiping Botanical Gardens, [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]]\n* UMS Botanical Garden, [[Kota Kinabalu]]\n* Zaharah Botanical Gardens, [[Johor Bahru]]\n* Johor Botanical Garden, [[Sri Medan]], [[Johor]]\n* [[National Botanical Garden Shah Alam]], [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor Darul Ehsan]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Malaysia|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of botanical gardens by country|Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Lists of tourist attractions in Malaysia|Botanical gardens]]\n", "text_old": "'''Botanical gardens in Malaysia''' have collections consisting entirely of Malaysia native and [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species; most have a collection that include plants from around the world. There are botanical gardens and [[Arboretum|arboreta]] in all states and territories of Malaysia, most are administered by local governments, some are privately owned.\n* Cameron Highlands Botanical Park, [[Cameron Highlands]]\n* Labuan Botanical Garden, [[Labuan Territory|Labuan]]\n* [[Malacca Botanical Garden]], [[Malacca]]\n* [[Penang Botanic Gardens]], [[Penang]]\n* Kuching Aquarium and Botanical Garden, [[Kuching]]\n* [[Putrajaya 